<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Ruling Party Rules out Mid-term Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's ruling Awami
(people's) League (AL) today ruled out the possibility of any
mid-term election in the country and said the opposition's talk
about such a poll was "uncalled-for".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a huge rally held here today, General Secretary of
the AL Zillur Rahman said that "We have been elected by the people
to serve them and we will leave office after completion of the
five-year term of our government."
</P>
<P>
Zillur Rahman alleged that the opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) was trying to create anarchy and
disturbances in the name of agitation over the price hike of
petroleum products, which is "necessary" in view of the price
increase on the international market.
</P>
<P>
The BNP and its allies enforced a countrywide general strike on
Sunday, in protest against the fuel price hike earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The opposition also chalked out a "tougher" program including a
protest march towards the Parliament on August 31.
</P>
<P>
"The government has proved to be complete failure in running
the state affairs and resolving people's problems in last 14
months," said the BNP chief Khaleda Zia, who also demanded a
mid-term election "at necessary time".
</P>
<P>
The AL took office on June 23 last year, following a triumph
over its arch rival BNP, led by former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia,
in the general election last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
