<HEADLINE> Kuwait Finalizes Study on Aluminum Smelter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has finalized an
assessment study of the socio-economic implications of a
proposed aluminum smelter project, the fourth to be operating in
the Arab world, Kuwait News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Institute of Scientific Research charged with the
mission said a detailed study on the project was completed in
coordination with Kuwait Industrial Bank and the state-owned
Kuwait Industries Company which will carry out the project.
</P>
<P>
The project was planned to be built in Kuwait Shuaiba
industrial area. The plant will have a designed annual capacity
of 200,000 tonnes of aluminum at a cost of 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It would be the fourth aluminum smelting plant in the Arab
world following the first in Bahrain with an annual output
capacity of 460,000 tonnes, the second in the United Arab Emirates
with an annual capacity of 245,000 tonnes and the third in Egypt
with an annual output of 170,000 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Industries Company's vice chairman Nasser Naki said
the finalization of the study was an important achievement for
the "strategic" project which he said would significantly boost
the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the project would lead to the establishment of a
series of side industries, promote the added value and the
balance of trade, in addition to its contribution to the
creation of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
He said it would play an important role in the country's
drive of diversification along with the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the presence of the project in Kuwait would also
help attract foreign investments which would as well help
attract modern technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
