<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The United States has agreed to grant 21 million
U.S. dollars in loans to help Lebanon combat the cultivation of
drugs and finance agricultural developments in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Daily Star reported Wednesday that the
loans will be mainly used in financing alternative crops in the
country's eastern Bekaa Valley where the drugs are grown.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's second most profitable bank Fransabank is
offering five percent of its shares for sale, the Daily Star
reported.
</P>
<P>
The offering, managed by the Beirut-based financial house,
Lebanon Invest, will add between 19.5 million to 21.6 million
U.S. dollars to Fransabank's unofficial capital of 59 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the offering marks a trend of shoring up capital
in a banking industry which is undergoing pressure to consolidate,
and diversify a funding base disproportionately dependent on high
yielding domestic treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
The shares are open to foreign buyers, but it can not be
quickly traded because every transaction has to be approved by the
central bank and takes a relatively long settlement procedure.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Tunisian government has offered a series of
privileges to foreign investment in Tunisia's agriculture.
</P>
<P>
These privileges include tax exemption of earnings and a
charge-free infrastructure for the piscinas or irrigation
projects, sources of the Tunisian agricultural
ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign firms in the Tunisian agricultural sector number
19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
