<HEADLINE> Discrimination Suit Becomes Class Action in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal judge has
allowed a lawsuit, filed in Florida in March 1996 by minorities
to accuse Motel 6 of discriminating against minorities, to proceed
as a class action.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit accuses the motel chain of refusing blacks and
other minorities rooms, giving them less desirable accommodations
and charging them higher rates, according to an Associated Press
report today.
</P>
<P>
The suit claims that as a matter of company policy, Motel 6
systematically discriminates against black guests and other
minorities. But the company said that it has never had a national
policy or practice which condones or tolerates discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Attorneys for the plaintiffs say there could be thousands who
might qualify for inclusion in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
A minority customer, Charles Boxley, said he and his fiancee
were told no rooms were available at a Baytown, Texas, Motel 6 in
March. But they found a white family checked in after them without
reservation.
</P>
<P>
Another customer, LaDonna Williams, said she and her family had
made telephone reservations for three nights at a Motel 6 in
Salinas, California, in July 1996 and been quoted a price of 26.99
dollars a night. When they arrived at the hotel, the clerk
insisted they pay 29.99 dollars in advance for all three nights.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of their stay, their luggage was taken out of
the room and they were told they had to leave because the room had
been rented to someone else.
</P>
<P>
The court battle began when two black sheriff's detectives
charged that in March 1994 they had been denied a room at the
Punta Gorda Motel 6 because of their race, the new agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
