<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: World Bank to Strengthen Role in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will dispatch
more staff to its resident mission in China and seek an enhanced
role in the country's rapid economic growth, a senior World Bank
official said.
</P>
<P>
The staff assigned by the Washington-based headquarters will
increase to 16 from the present level of 6-7 in two years, while
more local competent people will be hired, Yukon Huang, director
of China Program and chief of the Resident Mission in China, told
Xinhua here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Huang, an American national educated in Yale University, was
assigned to this new post in July after serving the World Bank for
over 20 years, including three years as director of the Country
Department III. He plans to leave for Beijing in late October.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is empowered to make 80 percent of the relevant
decisions, a privilege his predecessors did not enjoy. The change
came within the framework of the "Strategic Compact" introduced in
the world financial institution last year to improve its work
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will continue to provide assistance for China's
infrastructure, while seeking closer cooperation with the Chinese
on social, poverty and environmental fields, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 17 years, The World Bank approved loans totaling
27.973 billion U.S. dollars for 184 projects in China, according
to figures released by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Ninety percent of these projects are performing well as they
(the Chinese) are more careful and more focusing on doing
something," Huang noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the World Bank will pay more attention to
the central and interior parts of China, believed to be less
developed in comparison with the coastal region.
</P>
<P>
He said he had traveled to Hunan Province to "symbolically show
that the bank is going to do more lending in the central and
interior provinces."
</P>
<P>
As the soft loans from the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary lending arm, is
phasing out for China, and the Mission in China will concentrate
on fewer, better and more available projects, the new Mission
chief said.
</P>
<P>
"China is a country which can afford and should afford more
substantially for doing a lot in the social, poverty and
environmental areas," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
He said he is going to discuss with the Chinese authorities on
what the World Bank could do to share their social obligations in
terms of reemployment, housing and training.
</P>
<P>
"We are offering various options for Chinese enterprises,
private and state-run alike, to improve their competitiveness,"
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
He believed China will overcome the difficulties it faces at
this stage and sustain rapid economic growth in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"It will not because what they have right now is perfect. It
will because the confidence or what happened in the last 20 years
show they are also responsive to changes of circumstances," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not see the possibility that the World Bank
programs in China would be affected by ups and downs in the
Sino-U.S. relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
