<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Halves UK Apple Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Severe spring frosts and summer
hail storms have wiped out about half of Britain's apple crop and
UK apple growers are facing the worst harvest for 63 years, said
local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a normal annual crop of English apples is
about 300,000 tons, but this year the harvest is not expected to
exceed 150,000.
</P>
<P>
Output of traditional English apples, such as Cox and Bramley,
which account for the bulk of the crop, is estimated to be down
48 percent and 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of UK apple consumption is supplied by home
production in a good year.
</P>
<P>
Adrian Barlow, chairman of the English Cox Campaign, said the
crop outlook was the worst since 1934, the last time that orchards
were hit by such severe frosts, and many small producers could go
out of business.
</P>
<P>
Apple growers issued an appeal for help to consumers Tuesday
and asked people to stand by the industry and pay extra for the
fruit which has survived.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices are expected to be about 69 pence a pound, 40
percent higher than last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
