<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Energy to Be Used in Zimbabwe to Ease Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has identified more
than 15 projects for funding under the World Solar Program (WSP)
in Paris to ease rural energy problems, a senior Zimbabwean
official said today.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Energy Minister Enos Chikowore said the Zimbabwe
Solar Program 1996-2005 had prepared the projects with the
assistance of U.N. Development Program (UNDP) which would seek to
resolve energy problems in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when he officially opened a one-day
national stakeholders consultation workshop on the Zimbabwe Solar
Program (ZSP).
</P>
<P>
Stakeholders in the ZSP, he said, should work together to
ensure more bankable projects were developed for use in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
The program, to which the projects would be submited, was
adopted in June this year by the World Solar Commission chaired
by President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
''The important role that energy plays in the economic
development of any nation cannot be over-emphasised,'' said
Xhikowore, adding, ''There can be no meaningful development
without appropriate energy services.''
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of Zimbabwe's estimated 12.4 million
people living in rural areas depend on firewood and other
traditional fuels for their basic energy needs, resulting in
widespread environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government is keen to promote wide scale
development and utilisation of renewable energy technologies to
promote sustainable development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Workshop participants noted that solar energy played a major
role in providing appropriate forms of energy that help to
stimulate economic growth through small-scale industries, thereby
curbing rural-urban drift.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 people from the private sector, government
ministries and individuals attended the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
