<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Agrees to Pay Ex-Combatants Pensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
agreed to award a monthly tax-free pension of 2,000 Zimbabwe
Dollars (173 U.S.Dollars) to every war veteran and a lump sum
gratuity of 50,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (4,300 U.S.Dollars) as
recongnition for the sacrifices ex-combatants made in the fight
for the liberation of the country.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Leaders of the Zimbabwe Liberation War
 Veterans Association today, President Robert Mugabe told the
leaders of the association
that the cabinet had also agreed to extend free education and
health services to war veterans, their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
At a five-hour meeting Mugabe called to brief the war veterans
of the response from the cabinet to the demands they presented to
him last Thursday, Mugabe, who is patron of the War Veterans
Association, said the government had agreed that ex-combatants
should be given priority in the allocation of houses built by the
government in the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the monthly pension and gratuity, Mugabe said
the cabinet agreed with the war veterans on the figure of 2,000
Zimbabwe Dollars per individual, but said it is impossible for
the government to find the money to pay 500,000 Zimbabwe Dollars
gratuity demanded by the ex-combatants for every former freedom
fighter.
</P>
<P>
''We don ot have that kind of money,''he added.
</P>
<P>
In the past months, Zimbabwe's former freedom figthters held
demonstrations and resorted to picketing ruling ZANU (pf) party
and government offices, including the presidential residence,
demanding the government to pay their pension and gratuity.
</P>
</TEXT>
