<HEADLINE> Togolese President Asked to Mediate in Angola's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has
requested Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema to
mediate in the Angolan peace process, the official Angola News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Eyadema, Angolan President Eduardo Dos Santos
expressed the hope that the Togolese president would persuade the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) leader
Jonas Savimbi to offer more serious cooperation in the implementation
of the peace agreement, the report revealed.
</P>
<P>
The letter was passed on to Eyadema by Angola's Deputy
Minister of Interior Garcia Miala during his meeting with the
Togolese president in Lome, capital of Togo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Miala told the Angola News Agency that the
Angolan government hoped that President Eyadema would provide
valuable cooperation in resolving the Angolan conflicts because
he is not only rich in mediation experience but
also having maintained good personal relations with UNITA leader
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the Angolan peace process is in a
delicate situation, with some provisions of the Lusaka Peace
Agreement still outstanding.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Angolan President Dos Santos asked President
Eyadema to meet Savimbi to find out what the UNITA thinks at
present, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
President Eyadema promised to do his best to help Angola
defuse the existing dangers which will rekindle the flame of war,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Besides Togo, Miala will also visit Cote d'Ivoire, Zimbabwe,
Zambia and the Central Africa Republic to present Dos Santos'
letters to the presidents of these countries. 
</P>
