<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Car Workers Most Productive in Europe: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Nissan's UK car plant has toppled
General Motors' factory at Eisenach in Germany from its place as
Europe's most productive car factory.
</P>
<P>
A study of productivity among European car companies by the
Economist Intelligence Unit confirmed the resurgence of motor
manufacturing in Britain thanks mainly to the Japanese investment.
</P>
<P>
The British car factory worker, once a joke around the world,
is now among the most efficient in the industry, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
The Nissan plant at Sunderland, which began the Japanese
investment 10 years ago, knocked General Motors' off the top of
the European car makers' productivity table last year.
</P>
<P>
Each of Nissan's 4,100 workers on Wearside made an average of
73.2 vehicles per employee last year, easily outstripping the 67.7
for GM's older factory.
</P>
<P>
Toyota's Burnaston factory in Derbyshire, England moved up to
third place from seventh in 1995, with output per employee
climbing from 52.1 vehicles in 1995 to 66.9 last year.
</P>
<P>
Honda's Swindon factory in southern England retained fourth
place.
</P>
<P>
However, the huge gulf in efficiency between Japanese car
plants built over the past decade in the UK and longer established
British car factories shows little sign of diminishing.
</P>
<P>
The study showed Rover's biggest manufacturing plant, at
Longbridge near Birmingham, declining to 19th place near the
bottom of the league table, with the Unit describing productivity
as "generally poor."
</P>
<P>
The average Longbridge employee turned out just 28.2 cars last
year, although the survey admitted that by the end of 1996 the
rate was back up to 35 cars following the introduction of new
models.
</P>
<P>
It is believed here that the study will provide ammunition for
supporters of Britain as a manufacturing base for foreign
investors, in spite of the sharp rise in the value of sterling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
