<HEADLINE> Former US Agriculture Secretary Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal grand jury
today indicted former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy on charges
of allegedly taking more than 35,000 dollars, gifts, trips, sports
tickets and other favors from agri-businesses for himself, his
girl friend and his family when he was head of the department
between 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 39-count indictment came after a three-year investigation
by independent counsel Donald Smaltz.
</P>
<P>
The indictment alleges Espy accepted valuable items from
several firms doing business with the department, including Sun
Diamond Growers of California, a large agricultural cooperative;
Arkansas-based Tyson Foods Inc., the world's largest poultry
processor; Oglethorpe Power, a Georgia electric utility
cooperative; Smith-Barney, an investment, securities and brokerage
firm; Quaker Oats; and the Fernbank Museum.
</P>
<P>
He is also accused of concocting a pretense for traveling to
Dallas on official business by scheduling a meeting with a local
USDA investigator "for the purpose of justifying his presence" in
that city.
</P>
<P>
Espy also was charged of ordering the employee to delete
references to Tyson, his girlfriend, and the football game when
his travel itinerary for that day was requested by the USDA's
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
Espy resigned in December 1994, three months after an
independent counsel began his investigation. A former Mississippi
congressman, Espy has denied any criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
If convicted of all 39 charges and sentenced consecutively, he
could face a jail term of more than 100 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
