<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Ukraine Take Two Gold Each at Universiade Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MESSINA, Sicily, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Ukraine each took
two gold medals on the second day of the swimming tournament at the
University Games on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Igor Snitko of Ukraine claimed the gold medal of the men's 800
meters freestyle at a time of 8:05.13. Luiz Eduardo Lima of Brazil
won his country the first swimming medal at the games as he finished
second at 8:06.26. Marco Formentini of Italy snatched the bronze
medal at 8:06.37.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's second gold of the day came from Denis Silantvev who won
the men's 200 meters butterfly at 1:59.67. Jeffrey E. Julian of the
United States came home second at 2:00.49, followed by Przemyslaw
Pietucha of Canada in the third place at 2:00.66.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion and defending Universiade champion Penelope
Heyns of South Africa put up such a disappointing performance in the
women's 200 meters breaststroke that she finished only fourth in her
speciality.
</P>
<P>
No one would like to believe that Heyns could be so bad. Her time
of 2:32.13 was 5.15 seconds behind the Universiade record she set two
years ago at Fukuoka.
</P>
<P>
The event was won by Masami Tanaka of Japan who was timed at
2:30.24. Svitlana Bondarenko of Ukraine took the silver medal at
2:30.99 and the bronze medal went to Lenka Manhalova of Czech Republic
at 2:31.38.
</P>
<P>
Tatsuya Kinugsa added one gold to Japan's tally by winning the
men's 400 meters individual medley at 4:24.18. He was followed by
Michael Halika of Israel at 4:24.96. Stefano Battistelli of Italy was
third in 4:25.66.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday's competitions witnessed the fall of first
Universiade swimming record when Martina Moravcova of Slovakia clocked
a winning time of 1:59.96 in the women's 200 meters freestyle final.
</P>
<P>
The previous record of 2:00.34 was set by Connie van Bentum of the
Netherlands at Kobe, Japan, in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Kimberly A. Black of the United States finished behind Moravcova
for the silver medal while Luminita Dobrescu of Romania was third at
2:02.76.
</P>
<P>
The last event of Wednesday's swimming competitions was men's 4X200
meters freestyle relay. The American quartet led all the way to take
home the gold at 7:26.78. France and Germany each won their first
swimming medal by finishing second and third respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
