<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Disagrees with Using Force in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Ghana said today it would not
give nod to the use of force to reverse the coup in Sierra Leone
that toppled the legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
Military action in Sierra Leone would be "a little more
complicated", said Ghana's deputy foreign minister, adding that
"when we get to that stage, we will cross it."
</P>
<P>
However, he said if the United Nations is involved, Ghana will
follow the leadership of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"And we hope that it won't come to that. We do not wish to be
involved in an exercise that will lead to the lose of lives in an
African country," he said, quoted by the British Broadcasting
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
BBC did not say where the Ghanaian deputy foreign minister had
made the remarks, but foreign ministers of the member states of
the Economic Community of West African countries (ECOWAS) are
meeting in Abuja, capital of Nigeria to prepare for the ECOWAS
summit scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
West African countries have been trying to reinstate Sierra
Leone's ousted civilian government with a combination of three
measures -- dialogue, sanctions and the use of force since the
military seized power in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
To date, dialogue and sanctions have failed while the use of
force has not be taken up due to the split among member countries
of ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has expressed its support to any measures
that might be taken by ECOWAS to restore the legitimate
government of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of ECOWAS member countries will meet at a summit
tomorrow in the Nigerian capital of Abuja to decide what is to be
done to this end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
