<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Renews Demand for Taking Over NATO Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today renewed his demand for the taking over by Europeans of the
Naples-based Southern Command of NATO, which is now commanded by
an American admiral.
</P>
<P>
At a conference of French ambassadors stationed abroad, Chirac
said, "The Southern Command should be, in future, confided to a
European."
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that France will not return to the integrated
military structure of NATO unless the Southern Command is handed
over to Europeans by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
"It is the function of progress which will be realized in this
direction, and without letting ourselves closed in any timetable,
that France will determine its future relation with NATO," said
Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He said that the renovation of NATO, which was signed at the
Madrid summit of the trans-Atlantic military alliance in July,
"has cleared a big step toward the affirmation of the European
identity of defense" by NATO.
</P>
<P>
"But this affirmation of European identity should still go
ahead by a better sharing of responsibilities between Europeans
and Americans in the military structure of the organization,"
said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The United States has categorically rejected the French demand
for the handing over of the Southern Command, because the U.S.
Navy's Sixth Fleet makes up part of the NATO regional force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
