<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Die in Fresh Fighting between Somali Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Renewed intermittent clashes
between the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of the
Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) at Gurunjis village, 8 km south
of Baidoa Tuesday resulted in the death of at least 13 people.
</P>
<P>
Radio North Mogadishu today quoted RRA spokesman Mohamud Ali
Aden Qalinle as accusing the forces of Hussein Aidid of provoking
their militiamen at Gurunjis village and attacking their base
with 21 battle wagons.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle added that the 21 battle wagons of Hussein Aidid's men
have attacked their base from two directions, nine on one
direction and 12 on the other side.
</P>
<P>
The radio which supports Ali Mahdi, leader of north Mogadishu
claimed that the RRA forces have courageously defended their base
and destroyed two of what the spokesman called the enemy battle
wagons.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle admitted that his forces have lost two men while three
others sustained gun wounds during the two days' fighting.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also claimed that his forces have confiscated 21
assault rifles from Hussein Aidid's men during the fighting and
maintained control of their base.
</P>
<P>
There's no word yet, however, from Hussein Aidid's side over
the fighting. Hussein Aidid is leader of the South Mogadishu
faction pitting his forces against those of Ali Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, fresh clashes are reported to have broken out at
Dhiil Village and its surroundings, 32 km north of Huddor town
this morning, with casualties still unknown. According to
Qalinle, his forces have driven Hussein Aidid's men out of the
village, inflicting heavy losses on them.
</P>
<P>
This is the third round of fighting between the opposing sides
in the village located near the mountain land which is strategic
for the defense of Bakol region controlled by Hussein Aidid's men
since late 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Egyptian delegation led by Marwan Badri,
Assistant Foreign Secretary for the African Affairs, arrived
in Mogadishu today in a bid to mediate the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The four-member delegation will meet Hussein Aidid's faction
to discuss issues concerning reconciliation efforts in Somalia
during its two-day visit and it is also expected to visit north
Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
