<HEADLINE> France Adapts Itself to Changes in Africa: Chirac </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
said today that France is "adapting" itself and its defense
agreements with African countries to the big changes going on in
the black continent, but France will stay on in Africa as a
"primary partner."
</P>
<P>
"France plans, more than ever, to be present and active in
Africa, in fidelity, openness and modernity," Chirac told French
ambassadors stationed abroad at a conference in his presidential
palace.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government of France has announced a plan to
reduce thousands of French troops stationed in Africa and close
its military bases in the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
This came in the wake of a series of conflicts taking place in
French-speaking African countries this year -- former Zaire, the
Congo Republic and the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
"The recent crises have accelerated a real taking of conscience
of the need for Africans to take into their own hands the solving
of their difficulties," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed France's decision not to interfere in the
internal affairs of African countries through either political or
military means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
