<HEADLINE> Nestle Urged to Stop Selling Chocolate-Covered Toys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The attorneys general in
Minnesota and Connecticut today urged the candy giant Nestle to
stop selling chocolate-covered toys, fearing that the new
product may cause choking or death.
</P>
<P>
"This illegal product literally sugarcoats potential death and
injury -- wrapping in chocolate small toys that may cause choking
or worse," the Associated Press reported, citing what Connecticut
Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
Minnesota Attorney General Hubert Humphrey III said officials
were asking Nestle to "take all steps necessary to protect our
kids" and pull Nestle Magic from the market, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Last month Nestle began selling a ball of chocolate wrapped
around toy figures of Disney movie characters. Although health
officials have not found any safety problems in the candy, the
government said companies may race out candies that are a threat.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a Chicago company had to recall 5,000 chocolate eggs
after the government determined that the eggs pose a serious risk
that young children will choke on toy figures hidden inside.
</P>
<P>
The toys come in pieces that children are supposed to fit
together. But the Consumer Product Safety Commission said the
pieces were so small that young children could easily choke.
</P>
<P>
The commission on Monday advised parents who have bought the
Kinder Surprise chocolate eggs to take the toys away from children
under three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
