<HEADLINE> Greek PM Expresses Displeasure Over Dini's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today called his Italian counterpart Romano Prodi to
voice his displeasure over the statements by the country's
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today that
Greece had called for the retraction of the statements at the
highest diplomatic level.
</P>
<P>
Dini reportedly said earlier Tuesday after his talks with
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem in Rome that there were two
governments in Cyprus, namely the Greek Cypriot government and the
Turkish Cypriot government in the north of the island.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Foreign Ministry said in a statement Tuesday that
Dini's statements had no relation to existing reality, U.N.
resolutions, European Union (EU) decisions and the positions of
all Italian governments to date.
</P>
<P>
Reppas stressed that Athens regarded the Cyprus problem and the
Cyprus-EU accession talks as "crucial issues" for Greece's foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the relations between Greece and Italy would go
through "a crisis" if Rome followed a policy that opposed the EU
policy on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a
breakaway state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which
has only been recognized by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
