<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola to Offer Disbanded Soldiers Occupational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan Bureau of Job
Allocation and the International Labor Organization (ILO)
declared jointly today that an occupational education program for
the disbanded soldiers will be implemented this September.
</P>
<P>
The program is to cater for the demobilized soldiers with
occupational skills for better job choices, according to reports
from the Angola News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Charles Doucet, coordinator of the program, told the agency
that the program is targeted mainly at working out efficient
measures for the demobilized soldiers so as to maintain stability
in society.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen vacational education centers are to be set up
nationwide. Altogether seven majors including auto-mechanic,
carpenter, plumber and tailer are served to former soldiers with
different talent and schooling for a period of five months to 30
months.
</P>
<P>
The program is funded by United Nations Development Program,
with ILO providing the disbanded soldiers with working equipment
after their education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are about 100,000 demobilized army
men or fighters from the warring sides in Angola, most of whom
are poorly educated with few working skills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
