<HEADLINE> European Shares Recover on Strong Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
all reversed their recent declining trend and ended in the
positive ground today, ignoring Wall Street's weakness while
boosted by the dollar's rebound.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market closed 20.6 points higher
above the key 4,900-level at 4,906.9 although off the day's highs
and trading volumes were thin as many investors were still deterred
by recent extreme volatility.
</P>
<P>
An upturn in the futures market provided enough lift to push
the FTSE 100 back into positive territory after it slipped earlier
in thin trade.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended higher, within sight of the
4,000-point level after tumbling nearly 2.8 percent on Tuesday,
supported by dollar strength which is good for exporters.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index closed a quiet session with a rise of 36.33
points to stand at 3,995.66.
</P>
<P>
French stocks retreated early in the day along with New York,
and reacted to concerns over interest rates ahead of Thursday's
Franco-German meeting. However, the strengthening of the dollar
made the market rose sharply in late trading.
</P>
<P>
The market wiped out its morning losses and managed to finish
up 2.44 points at 2,871.7 on the CAC-40 index. 
</P>
</TEXT>
