<HEADLINE> UNITA Urged to Cooperate in Angolan Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Foreign Minister
Jaime Gama today called on the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) to abide by its promise in the
Lusaka Peace Accord to consolidate peace in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Gama made the statement to the press in Praia today after
concluding his visit to Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
As one of the three observer countries of the Angolan Peace
Process, he said, Portugal is watching closely the situation in
Angola like the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Portugal will not retreat from, or cease, its efforts in
ending armed clashes in Angola or in consolidating peace there,
Gama pledged.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister confirmed that he will meet tomorrow with
his Angolan counterpart Venancio de Moura to discuss bilateral
relations and the difficulties now facing the peace process in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the U.N. Security Council discussions on Angola
starting this week, Gama said, as a member nation of the Security
Council, observer on the Angolan Peace Process and participant of
peace-keeping forces in Angola, Portugal attaches great
importance to the U.N. meeting. 
</P>
