<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Independent Commission of Experts Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The total cost of the Independent
Commission of Experts for the 1997-2001 period has been
reestimated at 22 million Swiss francs (about 14.7 million US
dollars), resulting in a deficit of 17 million Swiss francs (about
11.4 million US dollars), according to a statement issued today in
Bern by the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Parliament in December 1996 authorized the commission
a 5-million-franc loan for a five-year duration to carry out its
research. But it has been determined that the actual cost for
1997-2001 will exceed that figure. Therefore the Swiss Federal
Council (government) will have to propose to Parliament to
authorize an additional loan of 17 million Swiss francs with the
1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The the mandate of the commission, created on December 13,
1996, is more comprehensive and complex than originally assumed.
Around 30 researchers will be hired in total. Another dozen work
under mandate contracts for the commission. Since launching its
work last March, the commission has evaluated sources available in
Switzerland and interviewed people who are said to have witnessed
Switzerland's role in World War Two. The commission will also try
to examine relevant information abroad in cooperation with foreign
researchers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
