<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ECOWAS Summit to Dwell on S. Leone: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- West African leaders will begin a
summit to work for the resolution on the Sierra Leonean crisis
and the future of the sub-region, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi said today.
</P>
<P>
The summit of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) will be "a historic meeting" which "ushers in peace for
Liberia and will test our ability to fight to restore peace to
Sierra Leone," said Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
Opening an ECOWAS foreign ministers meeting in Abuja, capital
of Nigeria, Ikimi said the two-day summit starting Thursday will
be seen mainly addressing the issue of Sierra Leone, which is a
big challenge for the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
It will also look into the future of the west African
peace-keeping force in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the meetings which have taken place earlier
among the chiefs of staff of our sub-region will give us the
further insights of how we shall deal with this subject matter as
peace and security are very crucial to our sub-region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers meeting began this morning to make
preparations for the coming summit. Before it, the planning
ministers of ECOWAS member countries have met to discuss the
economic future of the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Equally, chiefs of staff have been deliberating on the
restructuring and training of Liberia's security forces as well
as the situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
At press time, heads of state have arrived from Liberia,
Burkina Faso, Togo, Mali, Benin, Guinea, the Gambia and Guinea
Bissau. And ousted Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who represents Sierra
Leone, also arrived.
</P>
<P>
While more heads of state are expected to come later tonight,
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings will arrive tomorrow morning,
according to a Nigerian Television Authority report.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a Liberian president of an elected
government attended an ECOWAS summit since 1990 following the
outbreak of the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, the 16-member sub-regional economic bloc, has faced
with political crisis at all its meetings since 1990 and has to
dwell largely on the issue of conflict in one of its member
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
