<HEADLINE> Nobel Laureate Praises China's Economic Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Nobel laureate Merton H. Miller
recently lauded China's highly successly macroeconomic control
policies.
</P>
<P>
"What has impressed me most is that China has effectively
reduced inflation. The great success has been felt by all, even by
people in Chicago, " said Miller, a professor at University of
Chicago."
</P>
<P>
The Nobel laureate, who is attending the Ninth PACAP Finance in
Shanghai, also expressed confidence that China's economy will
continue to grow at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the conference, Professor Miller advanced the
idea of establishing a global clearing house for futures trading
in order to reduce trading costs and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that Shanghai is rapidly becoming a
major financial center of China and will soon become both a
regional and international center of finance. Hong Kong and
Shanghai will play their respective roles in China's economic
development, said the professor.
</P>
<P>
"China's financial sector has recorded remarkable progress, but
still has a long way to go. Many things must be accomplished,
especially the establishment of a legal framework," said Miller,
adding that China has a contingent of fine economists and he hopes
to have more opportunities to join them in exchanging ideas.
</P>
<P>
Miller, 82, has visited China six times and has maintained
close link with experts in China's economic community.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu Hongjun, president of Shanghai Institute of
International Finance, Miller has accepted an invitation to become
the institute's honorary president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
