<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Urged to Draft Framework for Tobacco Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
has been urged to formulate an international framework convention
on tobacco control by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The framework should focus on tobacco smuggling and
advertising, pricing and taxation, testing and reporting of toxic
constituents in tobacco products, and various other
tobacco-related issues, according to a resolution passed at
today's closing session of the 10th World Conference on Tobacco or
Health.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that the aforementioned issues are closely
related to the continuous growth in tobacco sales.
</P>
<P>
"Preparatory work for the framework has already started," said
WHO director-general Hiroshi Nakajima. "Hopefully, the support of
member countries will ensure its approval by the year 2000."
</P>
<P>
Drafting of the framework convention was a major topic of
discussion during the conference.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending the conference said that major tobacco
companies are using intensive sale promotions to increase their
sales volumes amongst women and young people.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for an international call for tobacco
control due to the fact that tobacco advertising is crossing via
satellite television and the Internet," said Dr. Konrad Jamrozik
from the University of Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
Allyn L. Taylor, from the U.S. Columbia University School of
Law, said that nonbinding resolutions and voluntary arrangements
will most likely be probably prove inadequate for controlling the
practices of the tobacco industry practices due to the sector's
intransigence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
