<HEADLINE> Three Overseas-Funded Trade Companies Open in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- China introduced yet another
move today to exhibit its firm attitude to join the World Trade
Organization (WTO) by granting approval for four overseas foreign
trade multinationals to establish three joint ventures with
Chinese colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The joint ventures, which will be the first group to
participate in China's foreign trade sector, will be based at
Pudong New Area in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Opening ceremonies for the ventures were held today in
Shanghai. Wu Yi, Chinese minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, and Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shan, deputy minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, who also attended the ceremonies, said approval of
the ventures represents a breakthrough in China's policy on
overseas investment, and efforts to reform its foreign trade
system.
</P>
<P>
The four foreign companies, which have long been major trade
partners of China, include Mitsubishi Commercial Corporation of
Japan, American Continental Grain Company, the Sunkyong Co. and
Daewoo Corp. from the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Chinese partners include the Orient Intl. Group of Shanghai,
Shanghai Lansheng (Group) Co. Ltd, and China Technology Import and
Export Corp.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Deputy Mayor Jiang Yiren noted that the local
government will adopt measures to support the development of joint
ventures in order to pave the way for the further reform of
China's foreign trade companies.  
</P>
