<HEADLINE> Shanghai Completes Construction of World's Third Tallest Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Exterior construction of a
88-storey skyscraper, believed to the world's third tallest, was
completed today in Shanghai and the complex is scheduled open next
August.
</P>
<P>
The 420.5-meter tall Jinmao Bldg. was constructed at a cost of
540 million US dollars, with funds jointly provided by the 13
largest foreign trade companies in China and the Orient
International Group from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Jinmao is currently the tallest building in China, some 36.5
meters taller than the former recordholder, the 384-meter Diwang
(King of Land) Commercial Mansion in the south China city of
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
"The mushrooming skyscrapers are a symbol of the prosperous
real estate business in Shanghai," said Zhao Qizheng, director of
the Administrative Committee of the Pudong New Area in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai plans to construct the world's three tallest buildings
around the city's 468-meter Oriental Pearl TV Tower, currently the
world's third tallest structure.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 94-storey Shanghai World Financial Center,
which neighbors Jinmao, is scheduled for completion in the year
2001.
</P>
<P>
The financial center will be eight meters taller than the
Petronas Twin Towers in Kuala Lumper, Malaysia, the current
world recordholder at 451.9 meters, said Zhao.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the third tallest in Shanghai will be funded by
European companies, since both Japanese and United States financial
institutions provided funding for the first two structures."
according to Zhao.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has either completed or is currently constructing 220
skyscrapers since 1992, including 20 buildings approaching 200
meters in height.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
