<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Calls for Expanded Cotton Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
has urged various areas to improve and stabilize state cotton
marketing policies and further expand reform of the cotton
distribution system.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a National Cotton Conference which concluded
yesterday, the vice-premier said that policies and measures should
be adopted to encourage textile enterprises to use more
domestically-produced cotton and strive to strike balance between
cotton supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference convened by the State Council focused on
analyzing cotton production and this year's supply and demand, in
addition to planning for cotton purchase and supply in 1997 and
cotton production in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, noted
that the contradiction of cotton supply exceeding demand has been
alleviated nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that cotton is a strategic commodity which is a major
source of the rural income. Therefore, the state should continue to
control the marketing, management and price of cotton.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier urged various areas to further expand reform
of the cotton supply system and develop cotton trade markets. He
also called for efforts to readjust layout of cotton plantations.
</P>
</TEXT>
