<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Deploys Troops to Prevent Serb Police Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led Stabilization
Force (SFOR) said today that it has deployed troops in
northeastern Bosnia to prevent possible clashes between rival Serb
policemen.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR received indications Wednesday night that there could
be a potential confrontation between police loyal to Serb
President Biljana Plavsic and those supporting other Serb leaders,
said SPOR spokesman Major Chris Riley.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the SPOR American-led division based in Tuzla
deployed troops in the areas of their responsibility early this
morning "as a prudent measure in order to have the ability to
respond to violence should they occur," Riley said.
</P>
<P>
The SPOR spokesman refused to confirm reports that American
troops deployed to the Brcko police station came under attack and
were forced to retreat by hundreds of angry Serbs who threw stones
at them.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Brcko was "fluid and continue to develop," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Riley, later interviewed on BBC radio, admitted that one
American soldier was slightly wounded and the troops used tear gas
to disperse the crowd.
</P>
<P>
According to a UN spokesman, the local station of UN
international police monitors in Brcko was attacked early this
morning, with several windows smashed and 15 vehicles damaged. Two
police monitors were slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Office of High Representative said that
there was an attempt by police loyal to Plavsic to take over
police stations in the northeastern part of the Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
The OHR called both sides of the conflict not to resort to
violence to solve their difference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
