<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Officer Sentenced for Leaking Exam Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- An officer of the Hong Kong
Examination Authority (HKEA), who admitted having leaked exam
papers, was sentenced today by a district court to perform 220
hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
Mak Cheung-wah, 42, was also ordered by the Eastern Court to
pay 10,000 HK dollars (1,280 US dollars) for court costs.
</P>
<P>
Mak had pleaded guilty to one court of having permitted his
son, a candidate in this summer's Hong Kong Certificate of
Education Examination (HKCEE), to have access to exam papers and
marking schemes.
</P>
<P>
The matter was discovered by members of the marking panel, who
found that the answers given by Mak's son in the HKCEE were
strikingly similar to those in the marking schemes.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC) conducted
an investigation into the case involving leakage of exam papers.
</P>
<P>
Mak was dismissed from his post and his son's results were
canceled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
