<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Conglomerates in Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-two percent of South
Korea's top 50 conglomerates are in the process of restructuring
or planning to do so to overcome their management difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Trade-Investment Promotion Agency said in a
survey of the 50 conglomerates said that restructuring is focused
on debt reduction, financial structural improvement, subsidiary
realignment, employee layoffs, rational investments, and mergers
and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring is considered by the conglomerates as a
counter-measure to cope with the nationwide economic trouble.
</P>
<P>
At least seven conglomerates including Hanbo, Sammi and Kia
have gone bankrupt or semi-insolvent.
</P>
<P>
The efforts by these conglomerates were also prompted by the
government-initiated policies on structural reform.
</P>
<P>
The survey also said that 96 percent of conglomerates admitted
that excessive business expansion is harmful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
