<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Says One-China Policy Vital to Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- One-China policy will continue
to be a fundamental element of the relationship between Australia
and China and Australia's economic and trade ties with Taiwan will
be pursued within the framework of the one-China policy, Australia
said today.
</P>
<P>
In its first white paper on foreign affairs and trade released
today, the Australian government said China will remain one of
Australia's key ties in the next 15 years and its approach to
China will be based on shared interests and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Those principles provide the basis for a realistic framework
for the conduct of the relationship, offer the best prospects to
maximize shared economic interests, advance Australia's political
and strategic interests, and manage differences in a sensible and
practical way, the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
The 92-page white paper, released by Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer and Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer, said Australia and
China have important economic interests in common and that the
Australian government seeks an expanding economic partnership with
a rapidly-growing China.
</P>
<P>
China has been one of the major buyers of Australia's mineral
products, wool and farm products, and Australia has been China's
single largest overseas investment destination.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise trade exports will also continue to grow as China's
economy expands, the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
China's economy has been growing at about 10 percent annually
during the past 19 years.
</P>
<P>
"China is likely to be among the three or four largest
economies in the world in 15 years, and to be integrated into the
international economy through multilateral and regional mechanisms
such as the World Trade Organization (WTO) and APEC," the white
paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Australia continues to support China's accession to the WTO on
appropriate terms," the document said.
</P>
<P>
China's economic growth and integration is to be welcomed,
which could enhance the prosperity and stability of the region,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Political and economic relations between the two countries have
been expanding rapidly following Prime Minister John Howard's
China visit earlier this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
