<HEADLINE> Seoul Mayor Appointed as Opposition Party President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The small opposition Democratic
Party (DP) of South Korea appointed Seoul Mayor Cho Soon as party
president at its national convention held here today.
</P>
<P>
The appointment came two weeks after the Mayor declared his bid
for presidency in the December elections on DP's ticket.
</P>
<P>
Cho is the fourth contender to join the presidential race
following ruling party Chairman Lee Hoi-chang and two major
opposition leaders, Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil.
</P>
<P>
"I will make sure my appointment as party president leads to a
victory in the vote, and then I will steer the nation's economy in
the right direction," said Cho.
</P>
<P>
He assured his supporters that he will try his best to campaign
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Cho, a former deputy prime minister for economic affairs under
former president Roh Tae-woo, also promised that he will try hard
to change the tiny DP into a nationally-recognized political force
by admitting new party members from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
According to recent public opinion surveys, Cho is enjoying a
relatively high supporting rate, closely behind the front-runner
Kim Dae-jung from the major opposition National Congress for New
Politics.
</P>
<P>
Cho, who was elected Seoul Mayor in local elections two years
ago, must resign from the post before September 19, the deadline
for presidential candidates to give up their official posts.
</P>
</TEXT>
