<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Party Congress to Highlight Deng's Legacy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) is just around the corner and
speeches by Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central
Committee, has repeatedly raised the issue of "holding high the
banner".
</P>
<P>
"This is a critical issue that relates to the Party's orientation
and image and has a great bearing on the future and fate of
socialism," Jiang was quoted as saying in a May 29 speech at the
Party School of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The "banner" Jiang referred to is the theory of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics set forth by China's late
senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who passed away in February this year.
</P>
<P>
"The entire Party, particularly the high-ranking officials,
must unswervingly hold high the banner of Deng's theory with a
high degree of consciousness and firmness, and we must never alter
our position no matter the difficulties and risks which might
arise," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Veteran political analysts in Beijing note that Jiang's speech
concerning the banner issue actually conveys the main concepts of
a keynote political report he will present at the forthcoming
15th National Party Congress.
</P>
<P>
One analyst said: "It is also a political manifesto the
third generation of CPC leadership with Jiang Zemin at the core,
after the death of Deng Xiaoping, is presenting to the
entire world."
</P>
<P>
Another analyst commented that the CPC has always attached
utmost importance to the issue of "banner". The late Chairman Mao
Zedong, one of the founders of the CPC and the People's
Republic of China, once said: "A doctrine is just like the banner
(of a party)."
</P>
<P>
Beginning with its birth in 1921, the CPC adopted Marxism as
its banner, with Mao Zedong thought added to the banner during the
Seventh National Party Congress in 1945.
</P>
<P>
Since the Third Plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee in
1978 and through the Party's 12th, 13th and 14th national
congresses, the Party has again expanded the banner with Deng
Xiaoping's theory on building socialism with Chinese
characteristics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Features of Ancient Changsha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, Augest 28 (Xinhua) -- The ancient city of Changsha, a
city with a history of over 2,500 years in central China's Hunan
province, has stressed the protection of its traditional features
during its modernization process.
</P>
<P>
The renovation of old districts in many of China's ancient
cities often conflicts with the protection of historical and
cultural traditions.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the city's Mayor Qin Guangrong, Changsha
will exert every effort to coordinate related protection and build
a city with both a modern economy and traditional cultural
features.
</P>
<P>
"History, traditions and culture are like the soul of a city,
and any city would lose its attractiveness with the loss of
traditional features," said Qin.
</P>
<P>
The mayor noted that all the new construction projects in
Changsha will be required to give full consideration to protecting
traditional local features.
</P>
<P>
"Changsha is the only city in China, which has remained in the
same location throughout its history," said Qin, adding that the
histories of numerous cultural heritages have left their imprint
and made Changsha a unique city representing the regional culture
of Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Changsha, the capital of Hunan province, was amongst the first
group of cities the State Council listed as famous historical and
cultural ancient cities in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
