<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Announces Actions to Stop Manipulators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today announced various measures, including
stopping the lending of securities, to prevent foreign funds from
driving down the local stock market through manipulative
short-selling.
</P>
<P>
The government would take stern action against anyone found
doing anything against the interest of the country, Mahathir told
local editors here.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had evidence that these foreign funds,
including those managed by American financier George Soros, had
shifted their attention from the foreign exchange to the equities
market in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Local institutions and private investors "willing to join the
government" have been asked to buy actively on the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange (KLSE).
</P>
<P>
There would be "no limit" to the buying-in and billions of
ringgit would be committed in this exercise if necessary, Mahathir
said, according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
These actions, coupled with the "delivery before sale" ruling
governing the 100 stocks which make up the market's benchmark
Composite Index (CI) which took effect this morning, are expected
to have a massive impact against the manipulators.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he accepted having open markets and foreign
participation in the markets. "I even accept speculation in the
share market but I will not accept manipulation of the market," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Today, the CI plunged 35.74 points to 812.18 under continued
selling pressure.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the situation had reached a point where there was
a total dichotomy between the share market and the profitability
of the companies whose shares were listed on the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the "delivery before sale" ruling announced
Wednesday might have caused share prices to drop, the same result
would have been seen within two weeks or less if no action had
been taken.
</P>
<P>
While the actions being taken might "make some people unhappy
with us, we are going to see this through," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to allow these people to manipulate our
economy as if they have a right to have a free ride on us," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government's actions were justified because
when something legal was abused, it was the responsibility of the
government to make it illegal. "My view is that this level of
manipulation must be made illegal," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Malaysian investors to enter the market and
revive the stock exchange and said that prices were now so
attractive that local shares would be a good investment, just for
their dividend yield even if capital gains were overlooked.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysia's ringgit took a fresh beating today,
hitting its all-time low of 2.8800 in another volatile and
cautious bout of trading today.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit closed at 2.8850/00 against the U.S. dollar today,
a plunge of 590 points against Wednesday's close of 2.8260/10.
</P>
