<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Medicine Helps Smokers Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A new nicotine-free medicine has
proved highly effective in helping smokers quit smoking, according
a British scientist's comments at an ongoing international
conference.
</P>
<P>
Professor Martin Jarvis, representative from the Imperial
Cancer Research Fund, said that clinical applications show that
the medicine -- Bupropion -- enhances the efficacy of NRT
(nicotine replacement treatment).
</P>
<P>
Jarvis told participants in the 10th World Conference on
Tobacco or Health that Bupropion's effectiveness appears within
four weeks, a much shorter period than for NRT patches. However,
he noted that a combination of the two will further boost the
efficacy of treatment.
</P>
<P>
NRT's are widely used to ease nicotine dependency. To replace
cigarettes and lessen the discomfort involved in the process of
smoking cessation, NRT's provide a safe level of nicotine in the
form of chewing gum, patches, or nasal spray.
</P>
<P>
Bupropion is also used as an anti-depressant, and was licensed
for smoking cessation treatment this year in the United States,
according to Professor Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
He added the new medicine has high prospects as a new
generation of smoking cessation drug since it effectively eases
discomfort when smokers attempt to drop the habit.
</P>
<P>
However, Jarvis pointed out the effects of drugs are quite
limited in terms of smoking cessation. A person who really wants
to quit smoking must have determination combined with behavioral
intervention and drug therapy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
