<HEADLINE> SFOR Deploys Troops to Prevent Possible Serb Police Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led Stablization Force
(SFOR) said today it has deployed troops in the northeastern part
of Bosnia to prevent possible clashes between rival Serb policemen.
</P>
<P>
SFOR received indications last night that there could be a
potential confrontation between the policemen loyal to Serb
president Biljana Plavsic and those supporting other Serb leaders,
said SFOR spokesman Major Chris Riley.
</P>
<P>
SFOR's American-led division based in Tuzla deployed troops
this morning "as a prudent measure in order to have the ability to
respond to violences should they occur," Riley said.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR spokesman refused to confirm reports that American
troops deployed to the Brcko police station came under attack and
were forced to retreat when hundreds of angry Serbs threw stones
at them.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Brcko was "fluid and continues to develop," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. spokesman, the U.N. international police
monitors' station in Brcko was attacked early this morning, with
several windows smashed and 15 vehicles damaged. Two police
monitors were slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Office of High Representative said that
there was an attempt by the policemen loyal to Plavsic to take
over rival-controlled police stations in the northeastern part of
the Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
He urged both sides of the conflict not to resort to violence
in solving their differences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
