<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Countries Urged to Stop Using Tobacco Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and all
countries in the world were urged today to stop using tobacco,
according to a resolution adopted at a world conference here today.
</P>
<P>
They should list tobacco as a harmful substance and try to stop
produce and consume it, according to one of the resolutions,
passed at the 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health, which
closed in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Another resolution suggested the World Health Organization (WHO)
work out an international framework convention on smoking control
to reduce the global hazards, caused by tobacco, Prof. Niu Rushi,
vice-president of the academic committee of the conference
announced on the closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco would become a major threat to people's health along
with HIV/AIDS by the year 2025, if no effective measures were
taken on tobacco control," said Judith Mackay, a senior WHO
official and director of the Asian Consultancy on Tobacco Control,
who described the conference as an "enormous success."
</P>
<P>
The conference, with the theme of "Tobacco: the Growing
Epidemic" has attracted about 750 Chinese delegates and more than
950 delegates from overseas countries and regions, which were the
biggest numbers among all the previous conferences.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference discussed the tobacco
epidemiology, tobacco control, cessation, tobacco with youth and
women, tobacco economics, and laws and international conventions
on tobacco control during the five-day conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference has provided not only a good forum for the
international personnel on smoking control, but also a precious
opportunity for China to gain more insights in this field, said
secretary-general of the conference Prof. Liu Rushan.
</P>
<P>
"The conference, the first of its kind held in a developing
country, has seen a remarkable increase in the numbers of
delegates from the developing countries and of women delegates,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Albert Hirsch, chairman of 9th World Conference on Tobacco
and Health, announced that the next conference will be held in
Chicago in August, 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
