<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Economic Zones Lead South China Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Three of China's five special
economic zones have begun experimenting with the socialist market
economy as the preferential State policies that were exclusively
theirs are being granted to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Shenzhen, Zhuhai, and Shantou in Guangdong
province have been making the leap to economic reforms to try to
maintain their economic development lead.
</P>
<P>
The three had a combined GDP of 146 billion yuan last year,
which had increased more than the national average, and exports of
26.3 billion US dollars, 18 percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
They took the lead in introducing a modern enterprise system to
the lumbering state sector. Shenzhen has completely separated
administration from enterprise operations by setting up state
assets management institutions. Assets of state enterprises grew
from 50 billion yuan in 1992 to 132 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai has organized 19 enterprise groups that have more than a
billion yuan in annual sales each in an effort to improve
competition.
</P>
<P>
The three cities have also adopted a wage system for chairmen
and general managers of companies, in which they have full
financial responsibility for losses. Pilot work has begun on a
system in which employees own shares of their own enterprises, and
a reform of the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen was China's first special economic zone. It began this
year to allow overseas-funded enterprises to be treated just as
Chinese companies are. It also simplified checking procedures at
ports last year by adopting internationally accepted
practices. After that, the other two zones followed suit.
</P>
<P>
The cities were also the first to set up a social security
system, providing coverage for medical care, retirement benefits,
on-the-job injuries, and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
And they have opened five free-trade zones, one third of the
total for the entire country, to use more overseas investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Head of French Secret Police Nominated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The new head of the French secret
police the Direction of Surveillance of Territory (DST),
Jean-Jacques Pascal, will focus his work on the protection of
financial information from foreign espionage and the fight against
terrorism perpetuated by Islamic extremists in France.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro said today that Pascal, 54, who was
nominated this week by President Jacques Chirac as the new chief
of DST, was no stranger to the world of spies because he was head
of another major French intelligence department, the Renseignement
Generaux (RG), from 1990 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
The report said that since the fall of the Berlin Wall,
economic espionage has become the new major threat to France,
against which French counter-espionage agents are charged to fight.
</P>
<P>
Even the allies of France are relentlessly trying to obtain
information from French enterprises in the sensitive sectors such
as electronics, aeronautics and information, it said.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign companies are trying to obtain financial
information about these enterprises to decide their "hostile
take-over bid," said the report.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, the French government has banned some
aeronautics companies from selling their aircraft parts to
foreigners, in order not to let France's aeronautics technologies
fall into the hands of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
In operations against terrorism, the DST is in charge of
collecting information abroad on potential sources of terrorist
attacks against France, while the RG, now headed by Yves Bertrand,
a close friend of Pascal's, is in charge of searching Islamic
extremists' networks in France.
</P>
<P>
The last major operation by the DST abroad was the arrest of
international terrorist Carlos in Sudan by French agents in
mid-August, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian Islamic militant groups, which claimed
responsibility for the bombing of an RER underground train in
Paris last December, are one of the major headaches of French
intelligence services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
