<HEADLINE> Sino-German Meeting on Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Xie Zhenhua, director of China's
National Environmental Protection Agency (Nepa), held talks with
German Federal Minister for the Environment Dr. Angela Merkel
today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged views on global environmental protection, and
discussed Sino-German environmental cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour meeting, Xie briefed Merkel on measures
China has adopted and progress the country has made in
environmental protection. He said that China has strengthened its
legal system and launched a large-scale battle against pollution.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that China will increase funding, rigorously enforce
environmental laws and regulations, and extend the greatest
possible efforts to develop science and technology for
environmental protection during the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
Xie expressed the hope that Merkel's visit will enhance
understanding between the two sides, and promote cooperation in
environmental protection between the two countries to a higher
plateau. He noted that China and Germany have a vast range of
prospects for cooperation in the field.
</P>
<P>
Merkel expressed great interest in China's environmental
protection work and spoke highly of the country's efforts to fight
pollution. She said Germany is willing to cooperate fully with
China.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also discussed a unified stand during an
international environmental conference scheduled for December in
Kyoto, Japan.  
