<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Review Report on Economic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- China's economic and social
development gained impetus in the first seven months of the year,
according to members of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing a report on the economic situation so far this year,
NPC Standing Committee members Wu Shuqing and Liu Suinian noted
China has achieved a reasonably fast rate of economic development
and a low inflation rate in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
After a "soft landing" of the economy made possible by effective
macro-control measures taken last year, the national economy has
grown rapidly in 1997, they said.
</P>
<P>
China reported another successful summer grain harvest this
year. The country's economic structure has improved, imports and
exports have increased rapidly, prices are stable and income of
urban and rural residents has also increased, they added.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jinhua, member of the NPC Standing Committee, said that "it
is inspiring to hear that China's western areas are taking in more
and more investment from the central government and other
localities in the country, with a growth rate of 10.5 percentage
points higher than the areas in the east."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wu urged that a flexible, preferential policy be
worked out to promote more investment in the western region.
</P>
<P>
Participants also expressed their worries over the money-losing
state enterprises and unemployment, saying that many of
the issues in China's economy now are closely related to
enterprises, particularly the state businesses.
</P>
<P>
The key to the state enterprises lies in "separating daily
operations from administration," they stressed. Some of the
participants suggested that a share-holding system or a
share-holding cooperation system be introduced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
