<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Enterprises on Road to Higher Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- State-owned enterprises have
scored an early success in turning unprofitable operations into
money-makers in the first half of the year, according to a report
jointly issued today by the State Statistics Bureau, the State
Economic and Trade Commission and the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The state industry has maintained an increasing momentum in
production, with 483.5 billion yuan in value-added output, up 5.5
percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The sector registered 130.99 billion yuan in pre-tax profits
during the period, up 13.5 percent, with 12.09 billion yuan of net
profits left after meeting the deficits. The deficits accounted
for 34.5 percent of the total pre-tax profits, a drop of 3.8
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive efficiency index of the state industry was
81.4 percent, an increase of 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises owned by the central government reported better
results in the first half than those affiliated with the local
governments, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The firms owned by the central government earned 19.61 billion
yuan, up 50.4 percent and its losses valued at 10 billion yuan,
down 5.9 percent, 22.8 percentage points lower than the country's
average.
</P>
<P>
Local state-owned enterprises were still running at a loss,
with the deficit increasing by 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that the overall economic profits were
still hovering low. The majority of the small-scale state-owned
enterprises were in the red, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
