<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Foreigners from Running Theatrical Troupes in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Culture,
hoping to maintain order in the culture market, announced here
today that at present, China will not allow the establishment of
equity, contractual joint venture or solely overseas-funded
theatrical troupes, performing venues and broking institutions.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the ministry explained that, according to the
newly issued set of regulations on the management of commercial
performances, overseas investment is allowed in renovating and
setting up theaters but those investors can not participate in
operating the performing business and management.
</P>
<P>
If artists from the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region,
Macao, or Taiwan, or from foreign countries want to give
commercial performances, Chinese broking institutions will
undertake to take care of them, she said.
</P>
<P>
This aims at further flourishing cultural undertakings, she
stressed, adding that China will continue to increase cultural
exchanges with foreign countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
She said that commercial performance has become the main form
of China's theatrical shows. And some people worship money so
stage shows cater to mediocre and vulgar tastes, and some actors
and actresses ask for high fees for performances and some avoid
paying taxes, she added.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations are the first attempt to restore order on
the stage in China and they stipulate that all performances should
adhere to the policy of serving the people and socialism. Also
prohibited are shows that might endanger state security and social
stability, promote division among ethnic groups, or spread
pornography, superstition, or violence.
</P>
<P>
China has 57,000 theatrical troupes and 400 broking agencies
providing services and information in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
