<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Further Accelerated in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- China's dazzling economic
take-off has turned the country into a more urbanized society, as
the number of cities increased to 666 and the urban population hit
208.22 million in 1996, according to the latest survey results
from the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The ongoing urbanization trend has resulted in a 39 percent
increase in the number of cities over the figure in 1991, the SSB
report said.
</P>
<P>
Among those newly-established cities, mid-sized cities
registered the fastest growth, with the number growing to 298 in
1996 from 121 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Such a rapid growth of mid-sized cities reflects the Chinese
government's tight control over the development of big cities, the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the gap was further widened between the urbanization
level in the east and west, as the number of cities increased by
9.3 percent annually in the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, China's cities together generated a
GDP of 4.7 trillion yuan (about 567.1 billion U.S. dollars) in
1996, accounting for 68.6 percent of the total in the country.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the per capita GDP reached 9,236 yuan (about 1,112
U.S. dollars) in urban areas, which is 3,697 yuan higher than the
country's average.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, about one third of urban residents worked in the
tertiary industry, contributing 37.2 percent of the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Since the 14th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China in 1992, the infrastructure facilities have been largely
improved in the cities, with the proportion of afforested land
expanded from 2.8 percent in 1991 to the present 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that China's cities will absorb 68 million
migrant workers over the next 10 years, as well as an additional
200 million residents from rural areas, which also will swell city
population totals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
