<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Hold Seminar on Partnership for Peace Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Military and civilian officials
from eastern and western Europe will be able to compare notes on
joint relief missions when a seminar on NATO's Partnership for
Peace program is held in Ukraine early next month.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, to be held from September 1 to 3 at Kiev under the
sponsorship of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), will
specialize in air-borne emergency evacuation and rescue operations
and be aimed at fine tuning the coordination among the military
and such civilian departments as transport and health ministries.
</P>
<P>
Partnership for Peace program is NATO's cooperation program
with former Warsaw bloc countries and other non-NATO European
nations on regional defense issues.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will be attended by some 90 participants from 10 of
NATO's 16 members -- Belgium, Canada, Denmark, Germany, Greece,
the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Britain and the United States --
and from eight Partner of Peace program countries of Austria,
Belarus, Hungary, Poland, Romania, Slovenia, Sweden and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, a member of NATO's Mediterranean Dialogue, will also be
present at the seminar focusing on exchanges of practical and
conceptual experiences in aeromedical organization and operational
use of fixed and rotary wing aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
