<HEADLINE> Thai PM Calls for Parliament Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh today called on the parliament to support the
government's measures to solve the country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made this call during a debate at a joint meeting of
the Upper House and the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
The parliament members were also briefed on the country's
current economic situation during the debate by Chavalit's top
aides in charges of the country's economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Virabonsa Ramangura told the parliament
that Thailand is facing a tough economic situation and stabilizing
the financial institutions and the baht is among the urgent
problems that the government should solve.
</P>
<P>
Rising inflation and unemployment as well as declining tax
revenues will upset the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the government measures to tackle the country's economic
problems, Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya said that the
government has suspended operations of 58 finance firms, floated
the baht, cut the government budget, secured the international
aid, and raised the value added tax from six percent to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
At the press time, the debate is going on. The debate is
expected to reopen tomorrow if it could not finish today.
</P>
</TEXT>
