<HEADLINE> HK Roundtable Meeting to Promote Science, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- "It is a big topic on the
agenda to combine highly-developed science and technologies in the
mainland with the high-developed commerce and trade in Hong Kong
after the establishment of the Special Administrative Region
(SAR)," an official from China's State Science and Technology
Commission said here today.
</P>
<P>
Duan Ruichun, deputy secretary general of the commission, made
the comments when addressing the opening ceremony of a three-day
roundtable meeting here on the science and technology development
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Duan said that two task force groups in Beijing and south
China's Guangdong province had prepared survey reports "to make
recommendations to the institutions in the mainland and HKSAR to
join hands in the field on the basis of mutual benefit."
</P>
<P>
Among the topics raised at the opening session of the
discussions today were the raison d'etre for science and
technology development in Hong Kong, manpower development in the
field for a sustained economic development in Hong Kong and
coordination in the field between HKSAR and China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the opening ceremony here today were
S.Y. Chung, conveyor of the HKSAR's Executive Council, Hyung-sup
Choi, president of South Korea's Federation of Science and
Technology Societies, and Yongyuth Yuthavong, director of
Thailand's National Science and Technology Development Agency, and
Tsoi Pui Yuen, deputy director of the Department of Education,
Science and Technology of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch.
</P>
<P>
Along the local experts attending the meeting were C.C. Lin,
vice-president for research and development of the Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology, and James J. Liu, chief
executive officer of the Hong Kong Industrial Technology Center
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is one of the celebration events organized by the
local science and technology community for Hong Kong's
handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
