<HEADLINE> Japanese Symphony Orchestra to Perform in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A leading Japanese symphony
orchestra will make its China debut next month to mark the
forthcoming 25th anniversary of the normalization of relations
between Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
The Yomiuri Nippon Symphony Orchestra, widely-respected in
western countries for its performances, will play in Beijing on
September 26 and 27.
</P>
<P>
Shigeo Iwatani, minister of the Japanese Embassy in Beijing,
said the Japanese side will organize many events for the 25th
anniversary celebration, with the concert as the highlight.
</P>
<P>
"I eagerly hope Chinese audience will enjoy the symphony
concert performed by the first-rate conductor and musicians from
Japan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The orchestra was founded in April 1962 by three prominent news
organizations in Japan, the Yomiuri Shimbun, the Nippon Television
Network Corporation and the Yomiuri Telecasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Under the baton of Otaka Tadaaki, Kobayashi Mie and Yokoyama
Yukio will be featured performers at the concert.
</P>
<P>
World-famous conductors and musicians who have worked with the
Yomiuri Nippon Symphony Orchestra, include Lorin Maazel, and
violinists Zubin Mehta and Itzhak Perlman.  
