<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Moves to Expel Lawmaker from Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A presidential commission of Sri
Lanka has recommended to the cabinet that opposition
parliamentarian Wijeyapala Mendis be expelled from the parliament
after finding him guilty of abuse of power in the former
government.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by cabinet spokesman Mangala Samaraweera at
today's weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera also revealed that the commission, appointed by
President Chandrika Kumaratunga in 1995, also recommended that
Wijeyapala Mendis, Chandra Bandara, R. Paskaralingam and Akil
Mohamed be stripped of their civic rights for a period of seven
years.
</P>
<P>
Chandra Bandar was a former minister of power and energy in the
former United National Party (UNP) government which ruled the
country for 17 year.
</P>
<P>
Paskaralingam was former secretary to the treasury and Akil
Mohamed, former secretary to the Ministry of Power and Energy.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera said that as Bandar is now dead, no decision would
be taken on this matter.
</P>
<P>
He added that since it requires a two-third majority in
parliament to pass the commission's recommendations which would
bar the three for holding public office.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the UNP would cooperate with the government.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
