<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Deliberating Draft Law on Earthquake Precaution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A draft law on earthquake
precaution, control and reduction is being deliberated at the
ongoing session of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Committee members held that it is essential to work out and
implement a law governing earthquake precaution, as China is prone
to earthquakes and is experiencing the fifth seismological dynamic
period of this century.
</P>
<P>
Earthquake precaution should focus on monitoring and
forecasting, they noted. The law, therefore, should stipulate in
explicit terms that the government should increase investment in
an effort to update technology and equipment and to enhance
research and forecasting capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Many voiced concern over inadequate quality of civic building
projects in China, especially that of the residential
housing. They suggested the law place stricter demands on
quake-proofing requirements for buildings and mete still harsher
punishment on those projects that fail to meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
Some of the members suggested that knowledge of earthquakes be
spread so that damage or loss of human life and property could be
minimized.
</P>
<P>
They acknowledged that the draft bill is basically well-written
and could be promulgated as soon as some revisions are made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium's Car Damage Insurance Cost Stands High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Car damage claims in Belgium
are the second most costly in western Europe, only behind
neighboring Germany.
</P>
<P>
A study published in today's newspaper La Libre Belgique (The
Free Belgium) said that Belgian insurers have to pay out an
average 1,472 ECU (1,604 U.S. dollars) for each reported damage in
a car accident, while those in Germany pay out 1,796 ECU (1,957
dollars) for each damaged car.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by Gesamtverband der Deutschen
Versicherungswirtschaft (GDV), a German insurance association,
which attributed the high insurance cost to human cost in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A technician has to be paid for an average 315 ECU (343
dollars) in Germany for a single rescue mission whereas such cost
in Belgium is 66 ECU (71 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Towing away the damaged car from the accident scene costs 671
ECU (731 dollars) in Germany, while the same cost in Belgium is
278 ECU (303 dollars).
</P>
<P>
With an average reimbursement for damage at 1,372 ECU, the
Netherlands has the third highest car insurance cost in western
Europe, followed by France (1,165 ECU), Italy (909 ECU) and
Britain (889 ECU).
</P>
<P>
Spain has the lowest car insurance cost in western Europe with
the average car damage reimbursement standing at 571 ECU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK External Trade Rises in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
external trade in July this year increased over the same month
last year, according to official figures released today.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that the value of total exports in the month
rose by 3.6 percent over the same month last year to 136.6 billion
HK dollars (17.51 billion U.S. dollars), while the value of
imports rose by 9.0 percent to 151 billion HK dollars (19.36
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
July saw a visible trade deficit of 14.4 billion HK dollars
(1.79 billion U.S. dollars), equivalent to 9.5 percent of the
value of imports. This was larger than the corresponding deficit
of 6.6 billion HK dollars (0.85 billion U.S. dollars), equivalent
to 4.8 percent of the value of imports in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months of 1997, the value of total exports
increased by 3.3 percent over the same period last year, while the
value of imports showed an increase of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, a visible trade deficit of 110.8 billion
HK dollars (14.21 billion U.S. dollars) was recorded, which was
larger than the deficit of 90.4 billion HK dollars (11.59 billion
U.S. dollars) recorded in the same period in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
