<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister on Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said today that India's foreign policy based on what
Mahatma Gandhi and Nehru had enunciated has stood the test of time
and the time-honored principles would continue to guide the
country's diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
Initiating a discussion on India and the world at the Upper
House of Parliament here, Gujral said that India has always sided
with all those who were oppressed although it had to pay a heavy
price for its stand.
</P>
<P>
India had followed a policy of "simulation and defiance". While
simulating new ideas and new languages, India had defied and
refused to get overwhelmed when such a situation arose, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gujral recalled the contributions of the former Soviet Union in
building India's industry and said India's relationship with
Russia and other members of the Commonwealth of Independent States
was "extremely good", and that India's relations with the U.S.
were improving a great deal.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that India's relations with China were
improving and that India had chosen to accept Beijing's invitation
for attending the handover ceremony of Hong Kong to China instead
of a similar invitation from Britain for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Gujral called for strengthening economic cooperation with
Pakistan. He said that his government accorded the highest
priority to improving relations with neighbors and India's ties
with Bhutan, Sri Lanka, Nepal, the Maldives and Bangladesh were
very good.  
</P>
</TEXT>
