<HEADLINE> 167 Million New Coins to Ease Shortage in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority is to put another 167 million coins into circulation to
alleviate shortages, a spokesman for the authority said.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second batch issued since the handover of Hong
Kong on July 1, which sparked a rush for coins bearing the Queen's
head.
</P>
<P>
From March to June this year, the Monetary Authority put a net
total of 27 million additional 10-cent coins, 22.5 million 20-cent
coins and 14 million 50-cent coins into circulation.
</P>
<P>
Compared with last year, the number of coins in circulation in
June should have increased 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of new coins, 100 million, was made available
from July 28, but many of them directly went into collectors'
pockets due to their new designs in commemoration of the handover.
</P>
