<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Claimers Awaits Iraq's Compensation for War Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Public Authority
for the Assessment of Compensations (PAAC) for damages from the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait has said it was awaiting money to
compensate the second batch of claimers.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Board Chairman and Deputy Director General of PAAC Adel
Assem said in a statement that the money was expected to be
obtained after Iraq starts selling oil under the oil-for-food
formula which allowed it to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil in six-month period for humanitarian purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations set by the U.N. Compensation
Commission, the claims were divided into six categories. The
second batch of claimers fall into categories A and B - category A
concerns people who left Kuwait during the seven-month Iraqi
occupation while category C concerns personal damages up to
maximum 100,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food formula, Iraq provided 600 million
dollars, or 30 percent of its oil sale to the compensation fund
run by the Geneva-based Compensation Commission which in turn paid
to some Kuwaiti and foreign claimers earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The second batch groups 224,079 claims submitted by citizens
from over 70 countries, Assem said. The U.N. Compensation
Committee will pay maximum 2,500 dollars for every claim
classified under the second batch and the gross total will be
around 560 million dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
As of the second quarter this year, the commission has approved
more than 277,000 claims with a total amount awarded of about 2.1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait alone has filed claims totaling 130 billion dollars
including the costs of extinguishing oil well fires set by
retreating Iraqi troops before they were chased out by a U.S.-led
military coalition.
</P>
<P>
Most payments of compensation for the other categories have
been approved by the PAAC except for the category concerning
losses caused by burning oil wells which are estimated at some
610 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Corporations from around the world are seeking another 80
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
