<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary on Partnership with ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook today outlined the areas of Britain's partnership with
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address on "Southeast Asia and beyond: Britain's
Partners for the 21st Century" here this afternoon at the end of
his two-day visit to Malaysia, Cook spelt out six areas for such a
partnership, which covers economy, security, freedom of the
people, the United Nations, environment and drugs.
</P>
<P>
On economic partnership, Cook said Britain's economic
partnership with the region is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
Not only is Britain the leading European investor in Asia, it
is second only to the United States as non-Asian investors in the
region, Cook explained.
</P>
<P>
Security, he said, is another vital area for partnership:
British engagement in Southeast Asian security, in particular
through the Five Power Defense Arrangement, is "unique".
</P>
<P>
"Our security partnership is not restricted to Asia: all
countries with a significant defense capability need to exercise
it responsibly as members of the international community," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On freedom of the people, Cook said it is perhaps the most
important because it underpins all the others. "Human rights are a
fundamental of foreign policy," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the United Nations, Cook said the work of reform, to which
the new secretary general has firmly committed himself, is of the
highest importance.
</P>
<P>
"This is not just for economic reasons. A shrinking world needs
an effective political forum where the international community
can address the long or short term challenges which confront us,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed U.N. General Secretary Kofi Annan's focus on
Southeast Asia, saying the U.N. leader, more than any of his
predecessors, has demonstrated that he recognizes the crucial
importance of this region.
</P>
<P>
On environment, Cook said it is all too tempting not to tackle
this issue because the problems are not sudden or pressing or
urgent.
</P>
<P>
On drugs, he said drug traffickers do not stop at national
frontiers and international cooperation is vital to combating the
problem. He stressed the need for ASEAN help in bearing down on
drug trade.
</P>
<P>
Cook said global cooperation demands better mutual
understanding between cultures. He expressed the hope that his
six-point plan for partnership will contribute to better mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
Cook praised ASEAN for showing a valuable capacity to maintain
its diversity while developing a communal solidarity, saying this
success has come about against the background of a historic shift
of global economic focus towards the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign policy and trading patterns of Europe must adjust
to recognize this new balance of economic power," he said. "We
want to see Europe open to Asia in particular."
</P>
<P>
Before the address, Cook called on Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and discussed the enhancement of Malaysia-Britain
ties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Cook also held talks with Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim and Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah after the talks rebuffed Cook's stand on human rights,
saying Cook was wrong to insist that all countries should respect
the same fundamental set of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah told reporters: "I think in human rights, it is very
difficult to have one common yardstick that is universally
applicable. Each country has a unique domestic agenda and should
therefore be allowed to deal with its own problems."
</P>
<P>
Cook later left for Jakarta to continue his four-nation
Southeast Asian tour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
