<HEADLINE> Israeli Exports to Asia Increase Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli exports to Asia
climbed to 1.99 billion U.S. dollars in the first six months of
this year from 1.86 billion dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
A latest report published by the Israeli Industry and Trade
Ministry said that exports to Asia comprise 20 percent of all of
Israel's sales abroad, while imports from the Far East comprise
11 percent of its total imports.
</P>
<P>
In January-July period of 1997, Israeli imports from Asia
totaled 1.59 billion dollars, a 2.8 percent increase over the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to diversify its foreign trade, Israel has in the
past few years launched a vigorous public relations campaign in
the Far East focusing on China, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's current visit to Japan and
South Korea is a fresh move in the drive. In Seoul, Netanyahu and
his South Korean counterpart Kim Young Sam Wednesday signed two
agreements, one on telecommunications and the other on technical
cooperation, mainly in agricultural field.
</P>
<P>
Israel's trade with South Korea has increased rapidly and is
expected to surpass 1 billion dollars this year. In 1996, the
figure stood at 720 million dollars compared with 692 million
dollars in 1995, and 430 million dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries was only 151 million dollars
in 1991, a year before Israel re-opened its embassy in Seoul.
</P>
</TEXT>
