<HEADLINE> Australia Wins Contract For World's Lightest Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian researchers have
joined forces with one of the world's largest car manufacturers to
develop the world's lightest family car, Australian Science and
Technology Minister Perter McGauran announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Commonwealth Scientific and Industry
Research Organization (CSIRO), the country's national research
academy, and the Cooperative Research Center (CRC) for Alloy and
Solidification Technology (CAST) have won a contract to design and
supply magnesium engine brackets as part of a 148 million U.S.
dollar project by the U.S.-based Ford Motor company.
</P>
<P>
The new car, the P2000, will make extensive use of light
metals, including magnesium, to achieve a vehicle weight nearly 40
percent less than today's comparable vehicles, the minister said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The hybrid vehicle will incorporate an electronic drive as a
newly developed engine which is expected to achieve fuel
consumption of 3 liters per 100 kilometers. A prototype is
expected to be developed this year.
</P>
<P>
McGauran said the development of a light weight family car
would have significant environmental and economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
"Lighter vehicles cut fossil fuel consumption, pollution and
greenhouse gas emissions. In addition, magnesium is recyclable,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ford's decision to use Australian design capability
complements its recent decision to participate in the construction
of a pilot magnesium smelter at Gladstone in eastern Australia's
state of Queensland.
</P>
<P>
A commercial smelter is expected to be operational by 2002,
employing a permanent workforce of 300-400 and providing 1,000
jobs in downstream processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
