<HEADLINE> China on Japanese-US Military Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- "It does not go along with the
trend of the times for Japan and the US to strengthen their
military alliance and expand their military cooperation in the
Asian-Pacific region, because the region is enjoying a
comparatively stable political situation, sustainable economic
growth and active security dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang made the
remarks at a news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the Japanese-US Defense Cooperation
Guidelines which are being revised by the two countries, Tang said
that the Japanese-US military alliance is a bilateral arrangement
formed in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
If the pact goes beyond its original scope, Japan's neighbors
will be concerned, and the security situation in the region will
become complicated, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the guidelines touch upon the details of the Japanese-US
military cooperation, China, as a neighbor of Japan, has to pay
attention to them, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that Japan and the US should adopt a
prudent policy on the problem, and should not do anything that
will worry neighboring countries.  
</P>
