<HEADLINE> Lebanese Army Raids Car Thieves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese army launched
another raid against car thieves in the region of Baalbek in
eastern Lebanon, shooting dead a member of a Shiite Muslim clan on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
local newspaper the Daily Star reported today that an army
statement said the 23-year-old victim, Mohammed Naouaf Mokddad,
was killed "when he ignored warnings to stop."
</P>
<P>
It was the army's second sweep in two months in this
Shiite-dominated area hunting car thieves, drug-traffickers,
counterfeiters and bandits.
</P>
<P>
As news of Mokddad's death spread, his armed relatives took to
the streets, blocking roads with rocks and burning tires.
</P>
<P>
Car thefts have gone rampant in Lebanon. According to the army,
in one week alone this month in the capital of Beirut, 23 cars
were stolen.
</P>
<P>
The army had arrested two members of the Shiite Muslim clan,
the Daily Star quoted army sources as saying. One has been
sentenced to five years in prison for robbery and the other
accused of counterfeiting money.
</P>
<P>
The two were on a list of hundreds wanted by the Lebanese
authorities, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the army admitted that the suspected gang leader,
Tayfour Moqdad, remained in hiding. He is believed to be running a
network accused of stealing cars from Beirut and storing in
Baalbek. 
</P>
</TEXT>
