<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Residential Mortgage Records Rapid Growth in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new mortgage
lending rose rapidly in July this year, according to the latest
monthly survey conducted by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
</P>
<P>
During the month, gross new loans rose by 27.3 percent to 32.5
billion HK dollars (4.17 billion US dollars). The average size of
new loans rose to 1.94 million HK dollars compared with 1.88
million HK dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
Repayment of loans also increased sharply by 20.5 percent in
July but at a slower rate than loan growth. As a result, the
amount of outstanding loans rose by 3.9 percent to 395.4 billion
HK dollars (50.69 billion US dollars) in July, compared to 2.7
percent growth in June.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gross loans for the purchase of properties in
China's inland areas increased to 369 million HK dollars (47.31
million US dollars) in July from 181 million HK dollars (23.21
million US dollars) in June. The amount of outstanding loans rose
by 3.42 percent to 6.98 billion HK dollars (894.87 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Authority said the rapid growth of mortgage
lending in the month is a reflection of market conditions as they
were in May and early June.
</P>
<P>
"The property market has since cooled and demand for new loans
seems to have slowed in August. Nevertheless, outstanding loans in
August may continue to grow quite rapidly because of loan
approvals already in the pipeline. In view of this, the recent
move by some banks to increase their mortgage interest rates is
prudent," the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
