<HEADLINE> Flowers Excels Coffee as Major Exporter in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The flower industry ranks
third among the fastest-growing export sectors in Tanzania, only
behind minerals and tourism, overtaking coffee as Tanzania's main
agricultural foreign exchange earner soon.
</P>
<P>
Within the next five years, flower exports are expected to
generate around 100.8 million US dollars, which is about 13
percent of the current overall export proceeds, the local press
today quoted industry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The success will be achieved if the current growth rates are
maintained, sources said, adding that the flower industry's
present growth rate of 100 percent is projected to continue or
even increase six times by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Tanzania earned five million US dollars from flower
exports, a figure which exceeded the amount earned between 1987
and 1995 when flower export business started in large scale in
the country.
</P>
<P>
A flower businessman Heikki Niskala has said that if
floriculture in Tanzania continues to grow at its current rate,
it can, within the next five years, become the second after
Kenya, even the first biggest flower producer in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Coffee currently accounts for about 17 percent of the
country's export earnings. Two years ago, it brought in 133.5
million US Dollars, a figure the Tanzania Coffee Board predicted
to go down by about 35 percent last season because of reduced
output and unpredictable world market prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
