<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Lifts Internal Blockade of Bethlehem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- To ease the rising tension,
Israel today lifted the month-old internal closure of the West
Bank city of Bethlehem imposed following the July 30 twin
suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
From four O'clock this afternoon, residents of Bethlehem were
allowed to travel to other cities in the West Bank. But they are
still barred from entering Israel because the total closure on
the Palestinian territories remains in force.
</P>
<P>
Israeli citizens are also still banned from travelling to
Bethlehem, but several buses of Christian pilgrims were allowed
to enter the city to visit the traditional site of Jesus' birth.
</P>
<P>
Following two days of clashes between Palestinian protesters
and Israeli soldiers, in which about 10 Palestinians were
wounded, the situation in Bethlehem remained relatively quiet
today. But in the morning, Israeli security forces arrested 15
Palestinians suspected of participating in hostile activities.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided to lift the blockade of Bethlehem apparently
out of the rising tension and political pressures from the
European Union and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Until this afternoon, Bethlehem was the last West Bank city
that was still under the suffocating internal closure imposed
since the July 30 bombings which killed 16 people and wounded 170
others.
</P>
<P>
In Seoul of South Korea, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said that Israel extended the internal closure of
Bethlehem because it suspected that the masterminds of the
Jerusalem bombings were hiding in the city and attempting to
carry out more terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
The militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) claimed
responsibility for the twin bombings. And Palestinian police
uncovered a Hamas bomb factory not long before the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu charged that Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat was still not keeping his words to crack
down on terrorism and attempting to create an atmosphere of
crisis ahead of the pending visit by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the region early next month.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechaik, speaking during a
tour to the Golan Heights, also kept on pressuring the PNA to
combat terrorism. He said that Israel was trying to ease the
pressure within the Palestinian territories, because an
explosion of the situation would not benefit anyone.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the continuation of the peace process,
which has been frozen since Israel began in March building the
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem, was conditional on the
PNA's campaign against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy, attending a meeting of lawmakers
in the northern border town Kiryat Shimona, said he was in favor
of lifting the total closure of the Palestinian areas. But he,
too, stressed that the PNA should first step up security
cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
In the Gaza Strip today, Israeli soldiers and Palestinian
police conducted for the first time a successful joint rescue
exercise in case of bombing attacks and accidents.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli security officials still complained that the
PNA's willingness to conduct the exercise was aimed only at
showing the United States that it was conducting security
cooperation with Israel, although in fact the drill did not
include any anti-terrorism contents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
