<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Postpones Visit by US Women Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian authorities have
blocked a trip to Iran by a U.S. women delegation which was
scheduled to arrive here tonight, a senior U.N. official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The official who spoke on condition of anonymity told Xinhua
that the U.N. office in the capital of Tehran has been officially
informed of that the trip by the U.S. delegation has been
postponed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Iranian side gave no explanation of the
decision to postpone the trip.
</P>
<P>
Observers here analyzed that Tehran's postponement decision was
due to strong opposition from Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei,
who insisted that Iran would have normal relations with all
countries except the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
This may imply that the newly formed government of relatively
moderate President Mohammad Khatami was left with little leeway in
formulating its foreign policy, the observers said.
</P>
<P>
A group of five women - four Americans and a Canadian - set to
make the first seven-day trip to Iran in 17 years as the guests of
former Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani's daughter
Fatemeh Hashemi, who heads the Iranian Women's Solidarity
Association and the Women and International Social Affairs
Department of the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Iran has responded to a new U.S. call for direct talks between
the two arch enemies by saying Washington must show in practice
that it wants to end its hostility toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
The two countries broke off diplomatic ties April 7, 1980 in
the wake of the U.S. hostage crisis in which the Iranian
leadership was accused of masterminding the abduction of
U.S. embassy staff in Tehran following victory of the 1979 Islamic
revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
