<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Solicits Non-Communists' Opinions on Party Congress Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) recently convened a forum in
Beijing to solicit opinions from non-Communist figures on the
draft version of a keynote report to be presented to the upcoming
15th CPC National Congress.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central Committee,
presided over the August 1 forum, which was held at Zhongnanhai,
the central government compound. Leaders of China's non-Communist
parties, the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce and
figures without any party affiliation were invited to the forum.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan and Hu Jintao, both Standing Committee members of
the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, and other
senior Party officials including Wen Jiabao and Wang Zhaoguo
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the forum, Jiang briefly introduced the
report's drafting process and explained its main contents. He
asked all non-Communist figures present to freely express their
opinions on further revisions.
</P>
<P>
Speakers at the forum include Lei Jieqiong, chairwoman of the
Central Committee of the China Association for Promoting
Democracy, Lu Jiaxi, chairman of the Central Committee of the
Chinese Peasants and Workers Democratic Party, Cheng Siyuan,
representative of figures without any party affiliation, He Luli,
chairwoman of the Central Committee of the Revolutionary Committee
of the Chinese Kuomintang, and Ding Shisun, chairman of the
Central Committee of the China Democratic League.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic National Construction Association, Cai Zimin, chairman
of the Taiwan Democratic Self-Government League, Jing Shuping,
chairman of the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce,
Yang Jike, executive vice-chairman of the Central Committee of the
China Zhi Gong Party, and Xu Caidong, executive vice-chairman of
the Central Committee of the Jiu San Society, also addressed the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
All the speakers agreed that the report is a programmatic
document that reflects the determination of the Party Central
Committee with Jiang Zemin at the core to hold high the banner of
Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics and lead the entire Chinese people to greater
success in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
They described the report as "a solemn announcement by the
third generation of collective leadership of the CPC", "a great
strategic plan of the CPC Central Committee", and "a powerful
ideological weapon for unifying the Chinese people's thinking and
actions".
</P>
<P>
They praised the report for taking a lofty stand, considering
the overall situation, having a prominent theme and distinct
viewpoints, and presenting thorough and convincing analyses.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their full agreement and hearty support for the
draft report, which they said has defined China's path of future
development and reflected the common aspirations of the whole
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they also made some suggestions for further revision
of the report, which include further highlighting the historical
status and guiding role of the late leader Deng Xiaoping's theory
of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, improving the
Party style of work, building a clean government and intensifying the
anti-corruption struggle.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that the report attach more importance to
education on patriotism, science and technology, education,
aid-the-poor programs and work in environmental protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Solicits Non-Communists' Opinions on Party Congress Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
General Secretary Jiang Zemin delivered a speech after hearing
views from the non-Communist participants on the report, in which
he thanked them for offering a lot of pertinent remarks.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said their statements took into account the overall
situation of the nation and the people's interests while focusing
on China's grand goal of modernization.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that they were free to air their views and offer
proposals for solving knotty problems and controversial issues
that have arisen in China's social and economic development,
adding that all their opinions will contribute greatly to the
revision of the report.
</P>
<P>
The Party Central Committee will study each proposal and give
serious consideration to all of them, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Jiang went on to note that the system of multi-party
cooperation and political consultation constitutes one of China's
fundamental political systems, which bears Chinese characteristics
and is an important form of the country's socialist democratic
politics.
</P>
<P>
During the long process of revolution and construction, he
added, China reached an important political consensus, which was
profoundly summarized by Deng Xiaoping: There will be no socialism
or socialist modernization to speak of without democracy.
</P>
<P>
Many years of practice has proved that during the drafting of
major principles and policies concerning the state and social
development, soliciting opinions from the democratic party figures
and non-party personnel, engaging in comprehensive political
consultations and letting the non-Communists exercise democratic
supervision are of great importance for making policy decisions in
a scientific and democratic way, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Party Central Committee will continue its practice, he
said, and the greater, better and more effective efforts will be
made in this regard, so as to give scope to China's this political
advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
