<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Solicits Non-Communists' Opinions on Party Congress Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) recently convened a forum in
Beijing to solicit opinions from non-Communist figures on the
draft version of a keynote report to be presented to the upcoming
15th CPC National Congress.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central Committee,
officiated the August 1 forum, which was held at Zhongnanhai, the
central government compound. Leaders of China's non-Communist
parties, the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce and
personages without any party affiliation were invited to the forum.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan and Hu Jintao, both Standing Committee members of
the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, and other
senior Party officials including Wen Jiabao and Wang Zhaoguo also
attended the forum.
</P>
<P>
After hearing a brief introduction of the report's drafting
process and major contents by Jiang, a number of non-Communist
figures expressed their opinions on the draft report.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the report is a programmatic document that
reflects the determination of the Party Central Committee with
Jiang Zemin at the core to hold high the banner of Deng Xiaoping's
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics and lead
the entire Chinese people to greater success in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the forum, Jiang extended his gratitude to the
non-Communist figures for offering a lot of pertinent remarks on
the further revision of the draft report, and said that their
opinions would be taken into serious account.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the system of multi-party cooperation and
political consultation under the leadership of the CPC as "one of
China's fundamental political systems" with distinct Chinese
characteristics, and promised that the practice would be adhered
to and still greater, better and more effective efforts be made in
this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
