<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Government OKs Rural Electrification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government has
approved the rural electrification master plan which priorities
areas to be electrified within the next 15 years, the Zimbabwe
Electricity Supply Authority (ZESA) announced here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The plan will cost 460 million Zimbabwe Dollars (40 million
U.S. Dollars)
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the program would be in two phases with the
first one running to year 2002 involving 94 projects which would
see 200 rural centers being electrified.
</P>
<P>
The second phase would see 78 schemes covering 215 rural
service centers being linked to the grid from 2002 to 2007.
</P>
<P>
The authority said, "with funding from the African Development
Bank, a consultant was engaged to carry out the study in close
consultation with ZESA and the ministries of transport and energy
and local government and national housing."
</P>
<P>
A total of 28 centers were identified ahead of completion of
the master plan with nearly half of them being electrified while
the remainder were at various stages of completion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
