<HEADLINE> Race for SA National Party Leadership Likely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Western Cape Premier
Heunis Kriel, believed to be the heir-apparent after F.W. De
Klerk's resignation from the opposition National Party (NP)
Tuesday, has declined to make himself available as a successor.
</P>
<P>
"My political career dates from the same era as that of Mr. De
Klerk, it would therefore not be in the interest of the NP if I
was elected as leader of the party," local daily, The Citizen
quoted Kriel as reporting.
</P>
<P>
By last night, NP Executive Director Marthinus Van Schalkwyk,
37, remained the only confirmed candidate for the leadership, a
senior NP source said.
</P>
<P>
Several likely contenders, including Gauteng Province leader
Sam De Beer, have indicated they would need some time to make up
their minds, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Former South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha said Wednesday
that he would like to lead National Party if the party prepares
to return to the government of National Unity.
</P>
<P>
Botha, 65, holds the distinction of having been South Africa's
longest-serving foreign minister until he had to relinquish the
post after the first non-racial elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The National Party's electoral college is due to meet in Cape
Town on September to choose a new leader for the party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
