<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Earnings from Minerals up Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe last year produced
metals and minerals valued at over six billion Zimbabwean
dollars, about 800 million more than the previous year, the daily
The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. dollar equals to 11.5 Zimbabwean dollars.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the ministry of mines, environment and
tourism show that 24,699 kg of gold valued at about three billion
Zimbabwea dollars was produced last year. But gold earnings are
expected to plummet this year owing to the low price.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Zimbabwe produced 9,694 tonnes of nickel worth over
700 million, a decrease in both quantity and value from that
produced in 1995. The country produced 10,864 tonnes of nickel
in 1995 valued at more than 730 million Zimbabwe dollars.
</P>
<P>
Asbestos production declined last year but the value rose due
mainly to more aggressive marketing strategies. Zimbabwe
produced 165,494 tonnes of asbestos fibre worth some 715 million
Zimbabwean dollars last year against the previous year's high
production of 169,487 tonnes valued at just under 590 million
Zimbabwean dollars.
</P>
<P>
Coal production last year was about 5.1 million tonnes, down
from the previous year's 5.5 million tonnes. Of last year's
production some 4.7 million tonnes were sold raising in excess of
640 million Zimbabwean dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chromite is another mineral currently facing problems. Last
year 658,416 tonnes were produced valued at about 190 million
Zimbabwea dollars. This was a decrease from the previous year's
production of 707,433 tonnes worth about 200 million Zimbabwean
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The value of the country's diamonds rose from about 42 million
Zimbabwean dollars in 1995 to over 86 million Zimbabwean dollars.
Production also doubled from 204,416 carats to 437,266 carats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preserving Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tibet, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The pigeon dance almost sank into
complete oblivion eight years ago when Lodan, a folk artist living
in the seclusion of the densely forested Linzhi District of Tibet,
died.
</P>
<P>
Lodan was the only master of the exotic dance and could mimic
the moves of a pigeon to the music, flapping his hands,
moving with small steps, stretching his neck out and drawing it
back, and swirling about.
</P>
<P>
Experts on Tibetan cultural heritage visited him numerous times
over a period of several years, but Lodan refused to utter a
single word about the dance. Finally, they encouraged him
to talk in 1989. However, a year later, he died.
</P>
<P>
"This was one of our numerous attempts to preserve Tibetan
cultural treasures," says Dandzim Cering, 53, Director of the
Tibetan National Art Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
"Before the peaceful liberation of Tibet in 1959, Tibetan
artists were so poor that, only by performing for the privileged
class, could they get food and money," he recalls.
</P>
<P>
After Tibet was liberated, many Tibetan young people were sent
to colleges in other parts of China for further study of
art. Dandzim Cering himself went to the Central Institute of
Nationalities to study dance.
</P>
<P>
"The Dalai Lama, who rebelled in 1959, is utterly wrong when he
says that the Tibetan culture has been ruined," says Dandzim
Cering. "He has lived in exile for nearly 40 years, and is
unfamiliar with the current situation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Receives $2.5 Billion of ODA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam by June has received 2.5
billion U.S. dollars from the pledged official development
assistance (ODA).
</P>
<P>
The funds accounted for only 29 percent of the total amount,
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign creditors have committed 8 billion in ODA to Vietnam
since 1993, most of which has been formalized in agreements or
other legal documents.
</P>
<P>
These ODA funds are being used to boost capacity of the
country's institutional bodies, infrastructure and human resources
development, and the restoration and development of
socio-economic facilities.
</P>
<P>
However, VNA said, the disbursement of these funds are
reportedly slow.
</P>
<P>
More joint efforts are needed to resolve the slow
implementation of the ODA-funded projects and disbursement which
could delay the transfer of ODA pledged by international community
in the future, VNA added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
