<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kampala Roads Getting Safer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Driving in Kampala is getting
safer as roads accidents in the Ugandan capital chalked up a
markable decrease in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Roads accidents dropped by 62 percent from 3365 in the first
six month of last year to 1300 in the same period this year, The
New Vision daily paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Grace Turyagumanawe, Kampala traffic police boss, told Uganda
Taxi Operators' and Drivers' Association Tuesday that the
reduction is reached due to the vigilance of police.
</P>
<P>
Police reinforced road patrol and check on the driving
permits, and had detected a large amount of forged driving
permits and thus blocked unprofessional drivers on the roads.
</P>
<P>
Most traffic accidents occurred in evening, early in the
morning, mostly during the first two weeks of a month, he told
his audience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
