<HEADLINE> NATO to Resume Work After Summer Recess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is to discuss the Albanian issue and start
accessing the answers to the questionnaires by Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic next week after the summer break came to an end.
</P>
<P>
Permanent representatives to the 16-nation alliance will work
out the details as regards how to materialize its promise of
helping Albania reconstruct its military following the
dismantlement during the recent riots in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a three-storey building has been vacated inside the
compound of the NATO headquarters to accommodate the negotiators
from the three central and eastern European countries that have
been invited to join NATO in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
NATO officials will first evaluate the military planning of
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
NATO is also set to hold a regular ambassadorial meeting with
Russia, the first of its kind, within the framework of the new
Russia-NATO Permanent Joint Council.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers are expected to meet in Maastricht for
an informal meeting in early October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
