<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Unveils 15-year Foreign Affairs Blueprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia today released its
first ever foreign affairs and trade blueprint for the next 15
years, including a commitment to forging closer relationships with
the United States, Japan, China and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The 92 page-white paper on foreign and trade policy, entitled
"In the National Interest", set out the principles and priorities
of the country's foreign affairs and trade policy.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, jointly issued by Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer and Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer,
examined the key international challenges facing Australia over
the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The paper described the Asia-Pacific, and particularly East
Asia, as the government's highest foreign and trade policy
priority, and identified globalization and the continuing economic
rise of East Asia as the two most profound influences on
Australian foreign and trade policy over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
"The (Australian) government's judgment is that economic growth
in industrializing East Asia will continue at relatively high
levels over the next 15 years," the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
The white paper devoted much of its analysis to bilateral
relations between Australia and the United States, Japan, China,
Indonesia, and some other countries or regions.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Australia's alliance with the United States is
an asset both redefined and strengthened by the end of Cold War,
adding the success of key Australian security and economic
objectives is greatly influenced by the economic strength and
political influence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
It said the depth and quality of Australia's relationship with
Japan are vital to advancing the broad range of Australia's
security and economic objectives, and Australia is forging a
partnership of the highest quality with Japan.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said China's economic growth, "with attendant
confidence and enhanced influence, will be the most important
strategic development of the next 15 years."
</P>
<P>
"China will remain one of Australia's key relationships...and
the Australian government's approach to China will be based on
shared interests and mutual respect."
</P>
<P>
The one-China policy will continue to be a fundamental element
of the bilateral relationship and Australia's "important economic
and trade relationships with Taiwan ...will be pursued within the
framework of the one-China policy," the white paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
The white paper also includes a segment on national values
which said the rejection of racism was fundamental to Australia's
acceptance with the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"Racial discrimination is not only morally repugnant, it
repudiates Australia's best interests."
</P>
<P>
On human rights policy, the paper said Australia's objective
should be to make a practical difference, not posture.
</P>
<P>
Australia's priority is practical efforts that can directly
improve the human rights situation on the ground, which include
development cooperation programs, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0206 </DOCNO>
