<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, August 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- Kazakhstan will never accept any unilateral oil
exploration and exploitation in the disputed Caspian areas,
Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart Kemelevich Tokayev said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said at a press conference Kazakhstan advocates
dividing the Caspian Sea thoroughly by the central line, while
Russia prefers partial demarcation, leaving the central area for
administration and development by the five bordering countries.
(Kazakhstan-Russia-Caspian Sea)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's Social Democratic Party (SDP), a non-cabinet
ally of the Ruling Democratic Party (LDP), will seek the exclusion
of Taiwan from areas subject to the proposed new
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Kyodo News reported that the SDP will make its case in
negotiations with the LDP and New Party Sakigake, another
non-cabinet ally of the LDP. (Japan-Guidelines-SDP)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said today
he will seek another term as president of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) in next month's poll.
</P>
<P>
The LDP Executive Council said earlier this week that the party
will accept applications of candidates for the presidential race
September 8, ahead of the September 30 expiration of Hashimoto's
presidential term.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is widely expected to be re-elected on September 8
for a second two-year term as LDP president, since no rival
candidates are expected to challenge him for the
post. (Japan-Hashimoto-Reelection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- A Libyan wanted in connection with the 1986 bombing of
a Berlin discotheque frequented by U.S. soldiers has been
arrested in Rome, police said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said the Libyan, Musbah Abulghasem Eter, 40,
was arrested on Tuesday night by Italy's anti-terrorism squad,
which is known as DIGOS.
</P>
<P>
The disco bombing in then West Berlin killed two U.S. soldiers,
a Turkish woman, and injured more than 200 others, most of them
U.S. soldiers. (Libyan-Disco Bombing) 
</P>
