<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Economic Development And Ownership Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's economy has been
growing at an annual rate of 14 percent since 1992, thanks to
economic and ownership restructuring, according to Huang Ju,
secretary of the municipal party committee.
</P>
<P>
The state owns 99.5 percent of the electric power industry,
94.4 percent of iron and steel and 89 percent of transportation
and telecommunications, three pillar industries in the city. It
also has a large number of assets in basic facilities and high
technology developments.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of assets to liabilities in state-owned enterprises
decreases six to seven percentage points every year.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign capital used by Shanghai increased at a rate of
56.3 percent yearly from 1992 to 1996, a 16 percentage point
advantage compared to the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Exports of joint ventures, co-operative and wholly
foreign-funded ventures was more than 4 billion US dollars in
1996, accounting for 30.3 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Collectively-owned enterprises had 30.1 percent of the city's
total volume of retail sales in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of private businesses and self-employed people have
risen to 55,000 and 100,000 respectively, the former 17 times and
the latter 66 times 1992's figures. Average registered capital for
private enterprises reached 604,000 yuan (72,000 US
dollars). There are 3,148 foreign-funded enterprises in Shanghai
that were established since 1992, with 2 billion US dollars worth
of foreign capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
