<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Russia Enhance Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian-Russian Military
Reconnaissance Cooperative Treaty signed Tuesday does not mention
that the two countries will jointly conduct military
reconnaissance on a third country, said Ukrainian Minister of
Defense Oleksandr Kuzmuk.
</P>
<P>
Kuzmuk made the remarks during a press conference jointly held
with his Russian counterpart Ignor Sergeyev here today after their
talks.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine and Russia share secrets on military technology,
weaponry and so on, which makes the signing of the treaty
particularly important. The two countries are closely knitted with
it, the Ukrainian minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Sergeyev's visit to Ukraine, Kuzmuk said the talks
went on in an atmosphere of mutual understanding and both sides
wanted to include their cooperative relationship in the
fundamental treaties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Ukraine's entry into the collective defense
system of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), Kuzmuk
said that this is an issue to be deliberated within the range of
foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is a neutral and non-aligned country, Kuzmuk
reiterated. If it joined the Tashkent Collective Security Treaty,
it would change its stand as a non-aligned country.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian Minister of Defense held that Ukraine and Russia
should make joint efforts to upgrade their cooperation in military
industry.
</P>
<P>
He added that the closer the cooperation, the more benefits
both sides will share.
</P>
<P>
What Russia is most concerned is how to finish building supply
ships as soon as possible, Sergeyev said, noting this type of
ships will be used to transport submarine reactors.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Minister of Defense said that both sides had
exchanged views on a wide range of issues concerning military
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
