<HEADLINE> Brunei Sultan Leaves for Home after Malaysian Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Brunei Sultan Hassanal
Bolkiah left here today for home after a four-day state visit to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The sultan was seen off at the Kuala Lumpur International
Airport by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Bolkiah, who is also Brunei's prime minister,
held bilateral talks with Mahathir and the two sides agreed to
hold annual meetings between their heads of government starting
from this year.
</P>
<P>
Both countries also agreed that ASEAN member countries take an
integrated approach to face manipulation by currency speculators.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Brunei sultan addressed the Malaysian
National Chamber of Commerce and Industry, saying that Brunei
would emulate Malaysia's determination to attain developed nation
status by 2020.
</P>
<P>
He also gave a public lecture at the Institute of Diplomacy and
Foreign Relations, stressing the need for ASEAN to preserve the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The sultan proposed the creation of an ASEAN football league to
forge greater understanding between people of the region and his
proposal was welcomed by Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Bolkiah also inspected the Royal Malaysian
Air Force Base in Subang near here and was briefed on the base's
operations before taking a closer look at the air force's fleet of
fighter aircraft comprising Russian-made MiG-29s, British-made
Hawks 200s and 100s and the latest acquisition from the United
States, the F/A-18D Hornets.
</P>
<P>
The sultan's last visit to Malaysia was in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
