<HEADLINE> Britain Recognizes Importance of Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook today said his visit here was to assure Malaysia and
other ASEAN members that Britain fully recognized the importance
of this region.
</P>
<P>
Britain, no longer isolated in Europe under the new government
led by Tony Blair, is now a leading figure in the European Union,
he told reporters after talks with his Malaysian counterpart
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi here.
</P>
<P>
"We are able to act as a bridge between the European Union and
ASEAN, and Malaysia, as one of the influential members of ASEAN,
is well placed to be at the other end of that bridge," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain and Malaysia should build stronger ties based
on their existing close linkages.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now has nine members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
When asked about Myanmar's participation at the Second
Asia-Europe Meeting to be held in London in April next year, Cook
said the matter was yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
He said it had been agreed that membership in ASEM would be
based on the consensus of the group which had its inaugural summit
in March last year in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Cook said, "The question of the presence of Myanmar was one of
the issues that we discussed today. We'll continue to discuss this
in the months ahead although we have agreed that everybody has to
agree before any one country is given membership."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abdullah said there would be more opportunities to
engage Myanmar in discussions now that it was a member of ASEAN.
Myanmar, together with Laos, joined ASEAN last month.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said ASEAN had yet to make a decision on Myanmar's
participation in ASEM and that ASEAN foreign ministers would
discuss this at the earliest possible opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Cook arrived here Wednesday on a two-day visit to Malaysia.
</P>
</TEXT>
