<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SDP Wants Taiwan Excluded From Defense Guideline Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Social Democratic Party
(SDP), a non-cabinet ally of the Ruling Democratic Party (LDP),
will seek the exclusion of Taiwan from areas subject to the
proposed new Japan-United States defense cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Kyodo News reported that the SDP will make its case in
negotiations with the LDP and New Party Sakigake, another
non-cabinet ally of the LDP.
</P>
<P>
They will map out a common view on the replacement for the 1978
guidelines, Kyodo quoted SDP sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three parties failed to reach a consensus of the review of
the guidelines in previous negotiations as their view on the areas
covered by the new guidelines differed.
</P>
<P>
A LDP proposal, advanced by Taku Yamasaki, chairman of the
ruling party's Policy Affairs Research Council, said an emergency
under the new guidelines is closely linked to the concept of the
"Far East" stated in the 1960 Japan-U.S. security treaty.
</P>
<P>
The proposal suggested Taiwan would be in the area to be
covered by the new guidelines as the Japanese government had
defined the Far East under the security treaty as the area from
the Philippines northwards, including Japan and surrounding area,
Taiwan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The SDP says in its proposal that Taiwan should not be included.
</P>
<P>
"It is appropriate to assume that Taiwan should not be included
in areas to be covered (under the new guidelines) after the
restoration of diplomatic relations between Japan and China in
September 1972", the SDP proposal says.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the U.S. will hold a ministerial meeting September 24
in New York to complete a final report on the new guideline, which
would pave the way for Japan to provide a broad range of logistic
and noncombatant support to the U.S. military in case of
emergencies in as-yet-undefined "areas surrounding Japan." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stocks Plummet to Another Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine share prices today
plunged to another two-year record low on concerns over the
slowdown of the country's economy and the further devaluation of
the currency of peso.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Stock Exchange composite index, a basket of some
30 companies, plummeted 213.77 points, or 9 percent, to 2,070.26
points.
</P>
<P>
It is also the biggest decline in a single day this year,
bringing the all shares index to tumble 56.38 points to close at
684.71 points. Since the beginning of the year, the composite
index has fallen by 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4.430 billion shares worth some 88 million U.S.
dollars was traded. Losers outnumbered gainers 161:9, with 15
shares remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Commercial and industrial shares led the decline, going down
235.64 points to 2,960.01 points. They are followed by property
and mining sectors, which declined 190.58 and 136.13 points
respectively.
</P>
<P>
There are a lot of factors contributing to the plunge of the
stock market, one of them is the Gross National Product (GNP)
coming out for the first half of the year is lower than last year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine National Economic Development Authority said
today that during the first six months, the GNP grew by 5.7
percent and the Gross Domestic Product by 5.3 percent, indicating
a slowdown in the country's economy, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at the overall economic picture, it seems that
everything is negative. All the negative news is out there, " the
analysts said, adding the economic miracle supported by lower
interest rates, stable currency and good growth in the Philippines
has all gone.
</P>
<P>
To rescue the peso which has been under speculative attacks
since early July, the country's Central Bank had to raise its key
interest rates and liquidity reserves for commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the bank raised the liquidity reserves for
commercial banks from the previous five percent to eight percent
while the peso hit a record low of 30.2340 against one U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Charter change movement in the country also
fueled the decline of the stock market. President Fidel Ramos
recently stood out to voice his support for the Charter change
campaigns seeking to extend the term of elective officials
including him.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said foreign brokers dumped their shares amid fears
that the country would have political unrest if Ramos should
remain in power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
