<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Comments on Caspian Sea Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan will never accept
any unilateral oil exploration and exploitation in the disputed
Caspian areas, Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart Kemelevich Tokayev
said today.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said at a press conference Kazakhstan advocates
dividing the Caspian Sea thoroughly by the central line, while
Russia prefers partial demarcation, leaving the central area for
administration and development by the five bordering countries.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev called on the Russian government to reexamine the oil
exploitation project in areas that fall within Kazakh territory,
and stop any activity that may provoke international disputes.
</P>
<P>
The five countries bordering the Caspian Sea are Russia,
Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said Kazakhstan doesn't recognize the Taliban
government in Afghanistan. He called for an end in armed
conflicts, progress in the peace process for national
conciliation and the formation of a government on the basis of
negotiations acceptable to all sides. 
</P>
