<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Suspend Passports Issued by Former Soviet Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine is to suspend the effect of
passports issued by the former Soviet Union from January 1, 1998,
Ukrainian Interfax News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Passport service and consultations departments of the Interior
Ministry will begin to call in all the passports held by former
Soviet Union citizens and service passports in the 01 and 02
categories from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
After the independence of Ukraine, passports held by former
Soviet Union citizens are granted the same legal effects with
those issued by the Ukrainian government. And they can be used
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Passports held by citizens under the age of 18 will be changed
to children's permits. Ukrainian citizens' passports will be
issued according to relevant laws for free charge.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry has been entrusted to inform organizations
abroad of this new decision. It will be put into effect on the
same day of publication.  
</P>
</TEXT>
