<HEADLINE> 48 People Killed in Heavy Rains in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 28 (Xinhua) -- At least 48 people were killed
and 15,000 others displaced in the past two days in floods caused
by heavy rains in Pakistan, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 houses collapsed and 16,000 others were
partially damaged in the rain-hit eastern province of Punjab and
North West Frontier province, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains, which started Tuesday evening and continued
incessantly for more than 24 hours, caused serious flooding in
rivers and on roads and streets.
</P>
<P>
Some roads were damaged and the traffic was cut down. Several
road accidents occurred due to heavy rains, leaving more than a
dozen people dead and many others injured, according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
A Flood Relief Center has been established in the capital of
Islamabad to collect information on rivers' water position and
people affected by heavy rains across the country.
</P>
<P>
The army has been called out to help the affected people and
protect dams, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Following heavy rains in Islamabad and its twin city
Rawalpindi, said the reports, the city's administration had set up
a flood control room to monitor rain stricken areas and provide
food and medical aid for the affected people.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the rains had killed five people in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains hit the whole country in the past two days, but
there were so far no reports on the damage or casualty in the
southern province of Sindh and the southwestern province of
Balochistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
