<HEADLINE> Flood Deaths Rise to 28 in Southern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from floods in
Southern Thailand since last weekend has risen to 28, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead, 12 were killed in Chumphon Province, which was
the hardest hit by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Other deaths were reported in Trang, Ranong, Surat Thani,
Nakhon Si Thammarat and Yala provinces.
</P>
<P>
The damage caused by the floods so far was estimated at around
two billion baht (66.7 million U.S. dollars), according to the
Thai Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh inspected the
disaster area in Chumphon province on Wednesday and ordered the
urgent dispatch of food and medicine aid to the region.
</P>
<P>
The floods were easing in Southern Thailand, according to the
local press. Electricity supplies in Chumphon province have been
restored and some roads have reopened.
</P>
<P>
Southern railway lines are also expected to reopen soon.
</P>
<P>
Thai Interior Ministry officials said that without more
downpours, the floods will dwindle in two days.  
</P>
