<P>
The intervention on Wednesday was prompted by the shortage of
the dollar in the market due to speculation, said Satyendra Pyara
Shrestha, Governor of Nepal Rastra Bank (NRB).
</P>
<P>
The bank has refixed the buying and selling rates of the dollar
for Thursday at Rs 57.50 and Rs 58.05 respectively, which were
set at Rs 57.25 and Rs 57.80 for Wednesday and at Rs 56.75 and Rs
57.30 for Tuesday respectively.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the rate of the Nepali currency against the dollar
has more to do with the recent devaluation of the Indian currency
against the greenback, because the Nepali rupee is pegged to the
Indian rupee, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves held by the NRB has reached 46.332 billion
rupees (about 809 million dollars) by mid-July, said a press
communique of the NRB.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
