<HEADLINE> PSG Storms Back to Win in Champions' League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Paris Saint Germain stormed back
to win 5-0 over Steaua Bucharest in the Champions League
qualifying round Wednesday, though the UEFA turned its 3-2
first-leg win to a three-goal handicap as a punishment for the PSG
fielding a suspended player.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Rai, who played a hat-trick in the game, combined
with Frenchman Florian Maurice for a powerful strike force to tear
apart the Romanian defence.
</P>
<P>
Rai started the roll three minutes into the game from the
penalty spot when Florian Maurice was upended in the area.
</P>
<P>
Rai headed in his second 20 minutes later before Italian
inernational Marco Simone tied the aggregate scores in the 32nd
minute by slamming the ball with his left foot into the corner of
the net.
</P>
<P>
Maurice scored the winner four minutes from the break off a
fine pass from Leonardo. Five minutes earlier, he was deprived of
his first goal as Dutch referee Dik Jol ruled it a handball foul.
</P>
<P>
Rai finished his scoring 11 minutes after the break by netting
Leonardo's cross to seal the astonishing victory.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle tied Croatia Zagreb 2-2 to win 4-3 on aggregate
through Georgian international Temuri Ketsbaia's winner in the
final minute of extra time.
</P>
<P>
Faustino Asprilla put the England team ahead just before the
half-time from penalty spot when Solvio Maric was turned down in
the area. Croatian central defender Goran Juric was sent off for
the foul.
</P>
<P>
However, the Croatians managed to tie the score on aggregate
with double strikes in the second half despite playing one man
down.
</P>
<P>
Dario Simic equalised in the 59th with a fine header in close
range after a cross from the left side, and striker Igor
Cvitanovic made it 2-1 in the 90th minute.
</P>
<P>
In the extra time, substitute Temuri Ketsbaia collected
Asprilla's pass to score the winner to stop the match from heading
towards penalties.
</P>
<P>
In other matches on Wednesday, Barcelona of Spain won 1-0 over
Latvia's Skonto to make a 4-2 aggregate score with the solo goal
scored by Brazilian Sonny Anderson.
</P>
<P>
Argentine midfielder Roberto Sensini headed in two goals as AC
Parma beat Polish club Widzew Lodz 4-0 to advance 7-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's Broendby succeeded to beat Dynamo Kiev 1-0, but
failed to compensate a 4-2 down from the home leg against the
Ukrainian team.
</P>
<P>
Galatasaray doubled its lead in the first leg with another 4-1
victory over Swetzerland's Sion to advance, Olympiakos of Greece
tied with Mozyr of Belarus 2-2 to secure 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's Kosice held Spartak Moscow to a 0-0 tie in Moscow to
advance 2-1 overall and IFK Goteborg played Rangers 1-1 in Glasgow
to advance 4-1. 
</P>
