<HEADLINE> Prolonged Drought May Trigger Food Crisis in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Food crisis reportedly may rage
Indonesia due to the prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Sjarifuddin Baharsjah said the rain season
will come late November or early December, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Baharsjah, who met with President Soeharto Wednesday, said the
president reminds the people to be alert for any food shortage
that may occur around Ramada.
</P>
<P>
Ramada is the 9th month of the muhammadan year observed by
Moslem as a sacred month on each day of which strict fasting is
practiced from dawn to sunset.
</P>
<P>
Baharsjah said that the public rice stocks will probably run
out until the drought expectedly ends in December.
</P>
<P>
According the National Logistics Agency, the country's rice
stock now stood at 2.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The government, said Baharsjah, is planning to make artificial
rain to help farmers cope with drought if the current dry season
persists by October.
</P>
<P>
The minister earlier estimated that the drought will affect
some 300,000 hectares of rice fields in the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the last serious drought, a total of 544.422 hectares
of rice fields was affected, of which 161,144 hectares was totally
damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
