<HEADLINE> More Juveniles Turn to Crime in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 9,450 criminal cases
involving 13,072 children and youths were brought to the courts in
Thailand during the first six months of this year, according to
the Central Juvenile and Family Court.
</P>
<P>
The number of juvenile delinquency cases increased sharply this
year with thefts ranking first with 4,451 cases, followed by
amphetamine abuse with 2,793 cases, Wicha Mahakul, deputy chief
justice of the court, was quoted today by the local press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Last year, there were 8,399 criminal cases involving juveniles
during the corresponding period, Wicha said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the increase in the number of child crimes on rising
economic hardship and a rise in the number of broken families.
