<HEADLINE> FIFA Denies Hand in Alleged Logo Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The International Soccer
Federation (FIFA) said Wednesday that it has nothing to do with
piracy and mismanagement concerning the mascot of the under-17
FIFA World Championship, slated in Egypt on September 4 to 17.
</P>
<P>
The controversy over a logo named Tut started when Mohammed
Taab, a graphic artist and lecturer at Cairo University's faculty
of fine arts, told the Egyptian press last week that his Tut
design had been stolen and threatened to sue anyone who uses it.
</P>
<P>
Taab said that he has the documents to prove the advertising
company he worked for has sold his design to FIFA without his
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Hisham Azmy, member of committee for FIFA Youth Competitions,
said at a press conference Wednesday that FIFA's operation has
been "lawful and legal" throughout its dealing with the logo.
</P>
<P>
"FIFA has been lawful from the beginning and has absolutely no
part in piracy. Besides, we have never dealt with the logo in a
commercial," said Azmy, who is also general coordinator of the
Under-17 FIFA World Championship.
</P>
<P>
He said Mohammed Taab never contacted FIFA, which signed a
contract with the Egyptian Soccer Federation and Shereen Youssri,
head of Phoenix Advertising Company on August 8. The Egyptian
company has won the deal with the innocent-looking Tut.
</P>
<P>
Azmy, who first named the logo "Tut's Foot," said that FIFA has
supported Taab and sent its representative to investigate the case
in July. He said FIFA is working with Egypt in the file.
</P>
<P>
"FIFA has the responsibility to bring the controversy to an
end," he said.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA official also promised not to contract either Mohammed
Taab or Shereen Youssri pending a court decision.
</P>
<P>
As the World Championship approaches, Taab had begun a compaign
to expose a deal he made with Shereen's company which supposedly
promised him 50,000 Egyptian pounds (14,706 U.S. dollars) if FIFA
accepted his design and later refused to credit his authorship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
