<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Japan to Enhance parliamentary Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and Japan will work to
enhance inter-parliamentary contacts between the two nations, a
senior Ukranian official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Speaker of the Japanese Diet's (parliament) House
of Councillors Juro Saito, First Vice-Chairman of the Ukrainian
Supreme Soviet Alexandr Tkachenko voiced interest in setting up a
joint Ukrainian-Japanese Center to study the aftermath of the
Chernobyl nuclear disaster.
</P>
<P>
''Japan's experience in coping with the consequences of a
nuclear disaster could be applied in Ukraine in a bid to overcome
the Chernobyl problems,''said Tkachenko.
</P>
<P>
Saito, who arrived in Kiev Tuesday, said that to set up the
proposed center, approval will be required from the Japanese
government and parliament as well.
</P>
<P>
Saito was supposed to meet Ukraine's Parliamentary Speaker
Alexandr Moroz, but he was recently hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese House Speaker said Ukraine's evolution toward
democracy and market economy is a major factor in European and
global stability.
</P>
<P>
Saito also reaffirmed Japan's interests in helping Ukraine's
shaky economy.
</P>
<P>
''The two nations' prospects for furthering economic
cooperation appear quite bright with the potential for creating
joint ventures and establishing economic contacts,'' said
Ukrainian Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko, who met Saito on
the same day.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko said Japanese-Ukrainian economic relations may
prove most efficient in areas including the extraction of oil and
natural gas, upgrading Ukraine's oil refineries, building
Ukraine's highway network and producing electronics, construction
machinery and materials.
</P>
<P>
Saito expressed support for Pustovoitenko's idea of fostering
Japanese-Ukrainian joint ventures in Ukraine, but added that this
would require legislative efforts and adequate infrastructure on
the part of the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
In the end, Saito said the Japanese parliament will continue to
support Ukraine, particularly by rendering humanitarian and
financial aid and technical assistance to tackle the long-term
consequences of the Chernobyl nuclear accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
