<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Reiterates UN Line on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
today reaffirmed to his Greek counterpart Costas Simitis that
solutions to problems of the divided island of Cyprus must be
based on resolutions approved by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking via telephone, the two leaders agreed that both
countries should work together to make the talks between Cyprus
and the European Union proceed in a way that is in line with the
U.N.'s position regarding Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Prodi's office said the prime ministers
had "a friendly telephone conversation" and reaffirmed their
mutual desire for co-operation.
</P>
<P>
It also stated: "the two parties will strive so that the
European Union can proceed on these principles with a view to
negotiations for the island to join the EU."
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas warned after the
telephone conversation of a "crisis" in relations between the two
countries, unless Italy withdrew comments attributed to Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
Greece was outraged after Dini was reported in the Greek media
on Tuesday as telling Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem that "it was
recognized that there were two republics, two governments and two
presences on Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Reppas claimed relations would be "heading towards a
crisis" if Prodi stood by the remarks attributed to his foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It is not possible that they (the comments) represent
the policy of a member country of the European Union, and of a
friendly country."
</P>
<P>
The remarks were "entirely contrary to the policy adopted by
the European Union with the complete agreement and the support of
Italy," Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
Reppas called for the EU to keep to its decision regarding
Cyprus in negotiations scheduled for the start of 1998 on the
issue of Cyprus joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
Discussions over the future of Cyprus reached a dead-end
earlier this month after opposition from Ankara and the
Turkish-Cypriots over when to begin negotiations for Cyprus to
join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974. The Turkish mainland army
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in response
to a coup in Nicosia, which was aimed at joining the island with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus was declared in 1983
but it is recognized only by Ankara, which maintains up to 35,000
troops there.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots and Ankara strenuously oppose the Cypriot
government's bid to join the European Union, and have threatened
to integrate the breakaway north with Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
