<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Falls Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah weakened
further Wednesday, dropping 100 points against the U.S. dollar
amid eased liquidity, while local share prices continued to gain
ground, analysts and dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said rupiah supply was adequate following the maturing
of central bank papers totaling 976 billion rupiah (348.5 million
U.S. dollars) Wednesday and 800 billion rupiah (285.7 million U.S.
dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This forced the rupiah to weaken as people started buying
dollars again. Confidence in the rupiah has not yet returned as
the strengthening of the rupiah so far seems to be artificial,
supported by high interest rates," one local foreign exchange bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 2,780/2,800 against the U.S.
dollar, fell in a thin market to close at 2,875/2,890 on the back
of eased liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices rose slightly with the Jakarta stock
exchange composite index up 0.2 percent, or 1.224 points, to close
at 555.462 points, with a total turnover of 415.1 million shares
changing hands at 170.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the market is waiting for the central bank's next
move following the slight easing of liquidity since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating minister for economy and finance Saleh Afiff
reiterated Wednesday the government would maintain the current
tight monetary policy until the rupiah stabilized.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah fell to a historic low of 3,045 against the
greenback after the central bank floated the rupiah on August 14
in the wake of sustained speculative attacks on regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The currency started recovering following the central bank's
increase of interest rates on August 19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
