<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Albania Seek Repatriation Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Albanian and Italian officials held
a meeting here today to discuss the date and method for returning
an estimated 10,000 Albanian refugees living in Italy.
</P>
<P>
During the all-day meeting, a joint technical committee studied
the process by which groups of refugees could be returned to
specific regions of Albania, an Interior Ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
Tirana is committed to "concrete cooperation" with Rome to
ensure "the ordered and dignified implementation of the
repatriation operation," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government has decided to extend the August 31
deadline for repatriation for another two months at the request of
the Albanian government. Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said Wednesday that a final decision would be made at Friday's
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government, inaugurated in July after the
internationally monitored general elections in June, is asking for
a longer extension of the deadline, saying two months is not
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo said today in Tirana that
it would be unacceptable if Albanians in Italian refugee camps are
returned to their homeland only to find shelter in refugee camps
there.
</P>
<P>
But the Italian government faces growing pressure from the
opposition, which has accused it of giving in to Albania and is
urging firmer action against immigrants without permits. Public
complaints are also mounting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many of the Albanian immigrants do not want to
return, saying they would prefer to find work here and stay
in Italy indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
About 17,000 Albanians have fled to neighboring Italy since
spring, when a financial scandal triggered nationwide anarchy and
plunged the Balkan nation into a political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
A reported 7,000 have returned to their own country so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
