<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Woman Becomes "Mountain Goddess" Through Hard Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A 54-year-old woman in south
China's Guangdong province is well respected in her hometown and
referred to as a "mountain goddess" because she got rich by
cultivating barren hillsides.
</P>
<P>
On 46 ha of hillsides in Dingbao Township, Xinyi city, clusters
of litchis and longan hang heavy in the trees, while chickens
scratch about below them, and a pigpen overlooks a fishing pond at
the foot of the hills. And the owner of this "mountain ranch", Liu
Yanxian, earns more than 300,000 yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago however, none of the villagers believed that her
adventure would bear any fruit, when she turned to cultivating 20
ha of hillside waste.
</P>
<P>
She moved her 10-member family to the hills and started by
improving the hillsides and planting trees. It took three or four
years before the trees bore fruit, so she raised chickens, bees
and pigs, and grew grass beneath the trees to cover the shortage
of funds.
</P>
<P>
These short-term projects not only provided her livelihood, but
also provided extra capital to open up even more barren hills. In
1992, a mountain ranch began to take shape and she was able to
sign a contract for cultivating another 26 ha of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
She has spent nearly 500,000 yuan on 11,000 fruit trees, 15,000
chickens, 100 colonies of bees, 160 pigs, and a two-ha fish pond.
</P>
<P>
"The woman did make a fortune out of the desolate hills, she is
really a mountain goddess," said a local farmer, admiringly.
</P>
<P>
Liu attributes her success to good policy. The township
government granted a 20,000 yuan interest-free loan and a 50-year
lease on the land.
</P>
<P>
One consequence of all of this was that she was elected to the
provincial people's congress, and has presented five proposals,
one of which, for road improvements, resulted in an allocation of
150,000 yuan from higher up, to the surprise of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Her family still lives in the mountains, and the ambitious
woman plans to build a road round-the-maintain to improve the
environment and her mountain villa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970828.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
