<HEADLINE> Pension Insurance for More Shandong Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 28 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong province has
opened special individual bank accounts to provide pension
insurance for local workers and the number has now reached 4.8
million, according to an official with the province's social
insurance bureau.
</P>
<P>
The development of China's market economic system has sparked
an urgent need for the establishment of a social security system
protecting the working force throughout the nation. Shandong leads
the nation in the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
The Shandong provincial government introduced a social security
system for all contracted workers in the province in early
1986. The system has been gradually expanded to cover employees of
state-owned, private and foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Contributions to the pension insurance fund come from three
major sources -- the government, enterprises and employees
themselves. Employees are required to contribute 2.5 percent of
their salaries to fund pensions.
</P>
<P>
The Shandong government also considered unexpected factors
which might affect the actual income of pensioners and, in 1994,
introduced adjustment mechanisms to the system in order to
guarantee the basic living standards of retirees.
</P>
<P>
With the mechanism the amount of pensions is adjusted in
accordance with the level of inflation on July 1 each year.
</P>
<P>
"Shandong retirees now enjoy the fruits of social development
and are free of worry about future living conditions," according
to the official.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, some one million Shandong retirees received an average
monthly pension of 417.8 yuan (50 US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
