<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Australian scientists have been shocked by evidence of a
developing EL Nino effect that threatens Australia with a
catastrophic drought and perhaps the world's worst global climate
disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- A Pakistani shopping list including Anzac frigates and other
Australian defense equipment has created scope for a diplomatic
rift with India.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani diplomatic sources said yesterday that Air Marshal
Abbas Khattak, Chief of Pakistan's Air Force, would raise defense
purchases during a visit to Australia from September 16.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australia plans to use its first white paper on foreign
affairs and trade to promote Australia as a free nation and to
combat perceptions in Asia that it is racist.
</P>
<P>
The 80-page paper, to be released today, emphasizes that
Australia has "a predominantly European intellectual and cultural
heritage" but as a nation finds racial discrimination "morally
repugnant".
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Japan has officially confirmed its economy is in worse shape
than previously thought, yesterday sending long-term interest
rates plunging to a historic low and slashing 2 percent off the
value of the Tokyo stock market.
</P>
<P>
-- Australia should tread carefully before following the
aggressive strategies of such countries as Ireland, Singapore and
Malaysia, using tax breaks and other concessions, to attract
foreign investment in information technology industries,
Australian Communications Minister Richard Alston said yesterday.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
