<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muster, Majoli Bid Farewell to U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Thomas Muster and Iva Majoli
became the first seed victims of top five by losing their first
and second-rounder respectively at the U.S. Open tennis
championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fifth-seeded Muster of Austria, the 1995 French Open champion,
was toppled in the first-rounder by Briton Tim Henman 6-3, 7-6
(7-3), 4-6, 6-4, while fourth-seeded Majoli of Romania went to her
doom against Sandrine Testud of France in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Henman, who charged to the quarter-finals at Wimbledon this
summer, said "I did serve very well throughout the match, and the
result doesn't really surprise me at all."
</P>
<P>
"He has great potential and he has a very stylish game,"
admitted Muster who has won 44 career singles titles.
</P>
<P>
Henman's win was immediately followed Testud's triumph at
Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Testud beat French Open champion Majoli of Romania 6-4, 2-6,
6-1, the second time in five days after her victory in last
Friday's semifinals of the U.S. Women's Hardcourt Championships in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Sergi Bruguera of Spain stumbled on the brink of
loss before he rallied from two sets down to beat 167th-ranked
Australian Michael Tebbutt 3-6, 4-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Bruguera, twice French Open champion, remained the only bright
spot for Spain in the tournament. And he was still not ready to
celebrate the win, saying that "it wasn't my fault that I lost the
first two sets, because he was playing unreal tennis."
</P>
<P>
South African Wayne Ferreira suffered a similar torture of
losing first two sets before winning his first rounder against
Alberto Berasategui of Spain 6-7, 2-6, 6-3, 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
The first rounders witnessed a string of falls for Spain on
Wednesday as Juan Antonio Marin, Emilio Alvarez and Galo Blanco
all lost their matches.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Spaniards who had five berths in the men's 16
seeds, lost two of their top players when eighth seed Carlos Moya
and 16th-seeded Albert Costa lost their first-round matches.
</P>
<P>
None of the other seeded players in the men's and women's
fields were threatened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tenth seed Marcelo Rios of Chile and 13th-seeded Australian
Patrick Rafter advanced in straight sets over Australian Luke
Smith and Andrei Medvedev of Ukraine respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, second-seeded Monica Seles, eighth seed
Anke Huber of Germany and ninth seed Mary Pierce of France all
advanced easily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
