<HEADLINE> Jansher Khan, Eyles into Hong Kong Open Squash Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Top seed and world number one
Jansher Khan from Pakistan, defending champion Rodney Eyles and
two other seeded players survived the first round competitions and
advanced into the top 16 at the Cathay Pacific Squash Open here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jansher Khan, who had won the Hong Kong event seven times
before being stopped in the final last year by Australian Eyles,
defeated 23rd-ranked Paul Gregory from Greece 15-2, 15-12, 15-9 to
win a berth in the top 16.
</P>
<P>
Jansher Khan will face 40th-ranked Nicholas Taylor from England
on Thursday, who won a hard-fought match 3-2 over 17th-ranked
Derek Ryan from Ireland. The two have never met before.
</P>
<P>
But defending champion Eyles had almost been ousted on
Wednesday. He was held to five games before winning over
25th-ranked Canadian Graham Ryding 15-17, 15-6, 8-15, 15-11, 15-9.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Eyles is to face 57th-ranked Peter Marshall from
England, who beat twelfth-ranked Anthony Hill from Australia 15-4,
15-6, 15-3 in just 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In other matches of the day, 20th-ranked Martin Heath from
Scotland beat fifth-ranked Simon Parke from England 15-5, 15-7,
15-9.
</P>
<P>
Paul Johnson from England, ranked 22nd in the world, downed
seventh-ranked compatriot Chris Walker 15-8, 15-6, 9-15, 15-13.
</P>
<P>
The five-day, 74,000 U.S. dollars event closes on Sunday.
</P>
