<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Loses Contact with Earth-Observation Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Aeronautics
and Space Administration (NASA) has lost contact with a 64.8
million U.S. dollars Earth-observation satellite since Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, which was named as Lewis and positioned in orbit
320 km high just four days ago, was spinning out of control at
about two revolutions per minute and cut off contact with ground
controllers.
</P>
<P>
The problem persisted today, said Sally Koris, spokeswoman for
the satellite's builder, TRW Space and Electronics Group.
</P>
<P>
The spin, which disrupted the sattellite's ability to generate
solar power, may have been caused by excessive firing of a
thruster on one side of the satellite.
</P>
<P>
The problem raised the potential for "loss of the mission," a
statement issued by NASA Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
"The solar arrays on Lewis were unable to generate full power
due to the spinning motion, and the batteries were discharged
below operational levels. Four subsequent attempts to contact the
spacecraft were unsuccessful," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Carrying instruments that could help monitor farm yields and
oil spills and assist with relief efforts during natural
disasters, the satellite was launched Friday from Vandenberg Air
Force Base, Calif.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, weighing some 450 kg, will have lost so much
velocity from atmospheric drag that it will plummet toward Earth
after three weeks if the problem persists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
