<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Keeps Going in Universiade Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CATANIA, Sicily, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan kept its winning
streak in the Universiade swimming tournament by taking two more gold
medals at Messina on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the opening day of the swimming tournament, Japan took
three gold medals. Wednesday's two gold strengthened Japan's lead on
swimming medal table.
</P>
<P>
The two golds were from Tatsuya Kinugasa in the men's 400 meters
individual medley and Masami Tanaka who beat her opponents including
double Olympic champion Penelope Heyns of South Africa in the women's
200 meters breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine also won two gold medals in the men's 800 meters freestyle
and men's 200 meters butterfly. The two winners were Igor Snitko and
Denis Silantev.
</P>
<P>
Today's competitions witnessed the first record-breaking
performance from Martina Moravcova of Slovakia who won the women's 200
meters freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Moravcova's winning time of 1:59.96 beat the previous Universiade
record of 2:00.34 set by Connie van Bentum of the Netherlands at Kobe
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The last swimming gold of the day was taken by the American quartet
who clocked 7:26.78 in the men's 4X200 meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
More countries wrote their names on the swimming medal table.
France, Brazil and Israel won a silver each while Germany got a bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
The fencing tournament produced one more gold on Wednesday.
Hungary, one of the world fencing powerhouses, finally proved
themselves by beating Russia 45-28 in the women's team epee final.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarians advanced into the final with a victory of 45-38 over
Germany. They were the obvious better side in the final and the 45-28
victory was the biggest gap being seen in the finals since the
beginning of the fencing tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team, which enjoyed a good luck by beating their
Chinese opponents 45-42 in the semi-finals, finished the runners-up
while China got their fourth fencing bronze medal with a 45-32 victory
over Germany in the third-place playoff.
</P>
<P>
The diving tournament saw another Chinese one-two finish in the
women's 3-meter springboard. Zhu Jinhong, who took part in the 1988
Seoul Olympic Games, totalled 507.57 points for the gold.
</P>
<P>
Lu Haisong, who won the 1-meter springboard title on Monday, added
one silver to her laurel after fading in the finals for a total of
493.47. Mexican Olympic veteran Maria Jo Alcala Izguerra took the
bronze with 479.40 points.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, China also had a one-two finish in the 1-meter
springboard through Lu Haisong and Chen Lixia. Today's victory
virtually gave China their third diving gold, the women's team title.
</P>
<P>
The athletics competitions continued on Wednesday with six gold
medals on offer. Mona Steigauf of Germany totalled 6,546 points to
win the title of heptathlon, the most difficult event in women's
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Irina Vostrikova of Russia and Marie Collonville of France took the
silver and bronze medals at 6,175 and 6,143 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Kislykh of Russia ran to his personal best of 13.44 seconds
to win the men's 110-meter hurdles. Belgian Jonathan Nsenga was
second at 13.51 while American Dudley Dorival placed third at 13.53.
</P>
<P>
The women's 200 meters and the women's discus throw were also won
by Russians. Ekaterina was timed 23.18 for the 200 meters title while
Natalia Sadova got the discus gold with a throw of 67.02 meters.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200 meters final was dominated by Americans. Gentry
Bradley clocked 20.48 seconds to beat his compatriot Anthony Wheeler
to the second place at 20.64. Anninos Marcoullides of Cyprus won his
country the sole medal so far at the University Games with a time of
20.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of Wednesday's athletics competitions was in men's
triple jump with two Cuban stars' appearence.
</P>
<P>
World champion Yoelbi Luis Quesada surpassed 17 meters barrier in
his five successful tries and secured the gold with a jump of 17.35
meters from his fourth attempt.
</P>
<P>
Aliecer Urrutia, bronze medalist at last month's Athen World
Championships, took the silver medal at 17.11. Robert Howard of the
United States was closly behind for the bronze medal with his best
jump of 17.08 meters.
</P>
<P>
The women's basketball semi-finals were played on Wednesday with
the United States beating Czech Republic 84-56 and Cuba defeating
Italy 81-71.
</P>
<P>
In the women's volleyball semi-finals, Russia advanced with a
hard-fought victory of 3-2. The Russians will take on the United
States in the final. The American team advanced with a 3-2 victory
over Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
