<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Move Toward Single Currency Irreversible: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The European economic, monetary
and financial commissioner today described as irreversible the
move toward single currency and economic union.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a forum at Alpbach, Austria, Yves-Thibault de Silguy
said: "In fact, the euro will become a reality within 492 days and
the process is now irreversible."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner cited as positive proof for the move the
lowering of price, inflation and budget deficit and stabilizing of
interest rate in the 15-nation union, according to a copy of his
speech available here.
</P>
<P>
Silguy said that in the early 1980s most EU countries suffered
from double-digit inflation whereas inflation is expected to
remain within 2.2 percent in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
He told forum participants that in the past five years average
interest rates within the EU has been declining and now with
long-term interest rates stabilize around 6 percent and short-term
rates at 4.6 percent, a result the commissioner described as
commitment by EU member states to the Amsterdam Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Another positive factor the commissioner cited at the forum was
the economic development. He said that the growth is expected to
reach 2.4 percent as compared with 1.6 percent last year among EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner predicted that most EU countries will have a
declined budget deficit to around or within 3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Silguy envisaged a future scenario for the single currency, the
euro, after January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the euro," the commissioner said, "will in the
first place be an international currency for international
transactions."
</P>
<P>
He said that the euro will be used, apart from EU countries,
primarily in three geographical zones -- the central and eastern
Europe, Africa and around the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
But the commissioner pointed to the exacting preparation for
the materialization of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
He said all parties concerned should take into full
consideration the difficulties to result from the creation of the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
He cited as potential problems compatibility, financial
mechanism and information network.
</P>
<P>
There even exists a risk, at least in theory, according to
Silguy. And that is the possible political and economic difference
between EU states and the International Monetary Fund as well as
between EU states and the Group-of-Seven industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Union will list out the countries to be in the
first wave of joining the single currency in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
But up till now, only Luxembourg has met both requirements
regulated by the Maastricht Treaty, that is, a country's budget
deficit cannot exceed 3 percent of its gross domestic product
(GDP) while its debt cannot exceed 60 percent of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, Denmark and the Netherlands are closing the gaps
toward meeting the requirements while Belgium, Luxembourg,
Ireland, Finland, Italy and the Netherlands have worked out
detailed plans concerning the transition toward the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
